dru: Cai Ying Weng Congtong patwakamani ki swa Siho kyaseasene ki kacalrisilrisiyane
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

dru: saka maposale si drosa ka caili ko tangilribatane kai kameane, ko tatonaganane pikai ki sapadrimane ki holrice pasi Sangpao la topeela pasi Yingcoming ko nagane. kikai satopelane tonagane, sasopilrane ko taki tosinalrelremeaneta kai ki tomawmase, ko taingeaane sapatothingalane kai Yingcoming tengatengane ka sako aikai kai Taiwang ka soadalepe kamani ko pimanemanane kai kadaengane Taiwang. lata sakai koini ki takaroaladhane pathagili, kai kameane, taparoa cocobongo padrima ko tapodrapalaneta. lai pato kamania ko ki soa Siho, papia ki Yingcoming, arakai ko saosaesakene kiaseasene, inilringa, ko tangilribatanenomi tara sopate ka idai ko caili, ko takitosinalremeane si kipakoalrialrialri, ngoalai koini, lalri patokamaniako ki soa kongkoane, si kiaseasene sabao iya nomiane
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

dru: wathingalako, pakelanga kai kameane, papiakikai ki tacekecekelaneta patolre, yakaiyana ko laomaomase ko kaipalraingi kiaseasene ko tapasalrivane lini. lakamani ko tokocingalreli naotara patokamani ki soa kongkoane kiaseasene sabao iya. nao tara topela pakabalrithi ko niposiranavane pakoalri pamatikoro, la kai kakathaane, amiyalringa kai, kikai amatikoroane akoalriane, taingeaane ka nibekacane kai ka nivothane, la kamani koini naotara sakai ko tacegeceganeli, si patopela tobavane ko takidremedremane iyako.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

dru: nao arakai ko madoai ko vaga, pelaela ko palolodane ko akiaseasenaneli ki Yingcoming. kikai kadaengane kai Taiwang, sa kainakela ki tarasopate ka idai ka caili, sakoa ka cekelenga si ikainga ko iyakaikai, kikoini laomaomase la ngisasingikai ko takidremedremanelini cekecele, yakai ko kadaengane lini, yakai ko vagalini, yakai ko kopalelini, laikai ko nidarepane ko kakodhane
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

dru: ki cekele. sakabilrilanenga, yakai ko kaika nipalraingane kicekele, la kekela singibadhane ko maelane ko laomaomase, ko takelanekai ki badhabadha wamalranga ravase ngitatoliniane sanaka laobobolo. la kikai napimanemanane, namani ko waolrongo kai Taiwang, la kidrikisinga kipakatoasenga kipaolrakao, la abadhabadhanga, saka cilri sana ka manemanenga, si kipothilinga matikoronga. lo pathagilita acegecege si ngiradekanenga ko kinaocekelane, alao arakai ko pasalrivane matikoroane ki palrapalra, ala ngilribate si kaesaesaesai, ai kathane lo kaiso polringao thingale si ngipapelaela konai iyakaiyana ko sakialibake thalradhane ki kinaocekelane iya. lai tara tokocingalreta pobelenge pelaela ko tangimiamiane, longimianga koini, ko mako ciacingalrenga, kai soa kongkoane itara pasingkidremedreme ngikakosaolri ngitatopela, amani koini ko patharevane kotacegeceganeli ikaikai kai kameane.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

dru: yakai ko nipacasane ko hongo Taiwang tongse amiya. ko asoalalanga, ko taiyane la iyakai, kadroa ko nipacasane tokakodhane kai Taiwang. toapathagili ko Helange, la pacongolo ko Cengcengkong,sa kela ko Laotia, yakai ko nitolamanemanane nitokakodhanane. kikai sakai ko takapairangane lini, aladarepe to hongo. kai Yingcoming, toalainga ko nadrama ikai ko kadaengane lini, yakainga ko tacekecekelane, wacegecegenga ko kakodhane ki cekele, arakai ko lrigilane thingalane, arakai ko kakodhane makilibalibake, macocongolo, pakelanga ki lagagane, ai kai kameane, arakainai ko taravasanenai, taka badhabadhanenai ngibabola pangilribate, ngoalai koini, ipatokamaniako ki soa kongkoane, papia ki Yingcoming sabao iya kiaseasene.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

dru: kai Helange si Cengcengkong arakai ko tarvasane lini kai Taiwang la drepete si papacai ki Pingpozoko, la kabebetethe ko tacekecekelane, sa obalrithinga kai Laotia, la motalovaivainga ko makaroroboro ladrepete si tosinalreme, saka Dripongongo ko waerece magagemegeme sanakamanemane, la topela ko kakodhane toadripongane sanaka manamane, toalai ki tamakaroroborane pakela ki Laotia la pacongolo aroparamoro, moaalra ko kakodhaneta. kikai nitarasopatane ka idai ka caili, loka moabalrithi kela kai Taiwang, toabadha ki kacalrisiane si arakai ko makakaraboro la ngisasingkai malrakai kadaengane, tokadroanga ko lamanemame ki Kacalrisiane. ngoalai koini, ipatokamaniako ki soa kongkoane, papia ki Yingcoming sabao iya kiaseasene.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

dru: kai Yingcomingco, arakai ko sidroadromane rathodo ki cekele, la arakai ko lrigilane ki sidroadromane kilibake ki kadaengane, lakai kabebebetethe capange ki lamanemane. ai, kikainga salri akabalrithingata ko kakodhane, kai Yinocomingco, kia pakaicilri sana ka manemane, kia drepete sikakodhane ko tangilralraingane lini, kadroanga ko kakodhanelini si kakodhane ki cekele, kaikiapatomanemanenga, ngoalai koini, ipatokamaniako ki soa kongkoane, papia ki Yinycoming sabao iya kiaseasene.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

dru: kai Kacalrisilrisiane, toalai ko nadroma, yakainga ko vagalini, ai toalainga sakela ko Dripongo, la arakai ko kakodhane ki Dripongo, latocilri ko kinacalrisianane, lamialrisa ka 1945 ka caili toalainga koini, pakaicilri kai soa kongkoane parakai ko vagalini kaoriva, la toalai koini moalodro kaolrao ko vaga. inilringa kai Pingpozoko, kadroanga ko vagalini. ko tangilribalribatane ki soakongkoane, lakai tokocingalre kakalithi si kai pakaolrao kikai sidroadromane ka kakodhane. ngoalai koini, ipatokamaniako ki soa kongkoane papia ki Yingcoming sabao iya kiaseasene
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

dru: saka nadroma, kai soa kongkoane, sa kaina thingale polringalringaw kai soaYamizoko, lapangokiboli kai soakongkoane, la totacilricilriane ki obolo ki dingki. toalainga koini, la kisabolo ko caemane, si matikoro toramoro. ngoalai koini, ipatokamaniako ki soa kongkoane papia ki Yamizoko sabao iya kiaseasene.
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government.

dru: kikai singi lalatadre lakela kai Taiwag si pakelanga kai, kai toacekele italitalriogane ka soa Pingpozoko asoalalanga kimocekele. sanaka wakela si ka singibadhane ko waerece ko kakodhane, tara moaalra ko tacekecekelane, twaolrao ko tasianeanane, ngoalai koini, ipatokama niako kisoa kongkoane papia ki swa Pingpozoko sabao iya kiaseasene.
english: Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

dru: kai takabalrithane kai kakodhane ki cekele, kikai cekeleta yakainga ko tatobalreane ko takitobiane ki Kacalrisilrisiane. kai kongkoane ka soatangadrane laikainga ko tapokaonanelini, la ikainga ko takisamolanelini. yakainga ko tadilaneta toramoro ko holrice ki Yingcoming, ai, kikai nidarepane kai holrice, kaikiataromarana ki soa kongkoane si malratokocingalre. lakonai, kadroa ko tatoracanganenai, kaimaka ngoelre, yakaiyana ko kaika takademelane. ngoalai koini, ipatokamaniako ki soa kongkoane papia ki Yingcoming sabao iya kiaseasene. kai Taiwang nimaiyaiyane ko maikaikai maibibo sana ka kakodhane, ai, pakelanga kai kameane, kai aodringadringadhane ki kinaomasane, kai akibolraane, kai sarakaiyane cekecekele, akipaelreane kicapili sanakamanemane patolre, kai kacalrisiane kia sobilriliyana toromaro kai maka toapapalra ki soadratatane. la kaiasasane, lo drele ki Kacalrisiane kai soadratane, kaina maolrao ko tosinalremeanelini mitaane ko kaika taosakenane. la kabekelaneana ko tapasikaiyane ki soa kongkoane, makalra toramro ko kipakoalrinomi matikoronomi, ko kainaka thingale ki soadrtatane si kipabalra. ngoalai koini ipatokamaniako ki Siho, papia nomiane ka Yingcoming, la kiaseasene sokobo sabao iya.
english: After the democratic transition, the country began to respond to the appeals of indigenous movements. The government made certain promises and efforts. Today, we have an Indigenous Peoples Basic Law that is quite advanced. However, government agencies have not given sufficient weight to this law. Our actions have not been fast enough, comprehensive enough or sound enough. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

dru: kai kadali kai takisamolanenai, ko tangilribatane maococongolo, kai sarawadrele ko kaika tapakelane kaongo, la kamaniko kipakoalrinomi, tengatengane ka sabao toramoro.
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

dru: kai ta kiaseasenane kai kameane, oono ngyaabalai toramoro, ai tai ngeane ka tatoaladhaneta topathagili. kainako siadrama, kai takipakoalrianenomi matikoro tara sopate ka idai ka caili, langokai ki sivavale ka pcase, niako vavalane ko vaga, si pakasopilri ko samadranenomi. ai, yakai ko tasidramaaneli, kai takiaseasenane kai kameane, taingeaane ka mitane makanaelre ka kinaocekelane, ka atoaladhaneta topathagili, makilibalibake, mapaceacepe ka maretetese.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

dru: la pacepaili, yarakaiyako ko lrigilanenomi ka Kacalrisiane, si pelaela kai raroboane kai kameane. iyakai ko vaga ki Taiyazoko, tangimiamiane loiyakovagalini amiya, la ko sakidalroane sbalay laiya. lo picocobongane ki balay si padrima ko s ka lingao. tangimiamiane si sakidalroane, yakai ko patharevane ko kakodhane. lo carongocongane pelaela. ko patengatengane si makisodalrodalromado, pasingia kidremedrememado matatoalrevegemodo. la mathingathingnle ko tangimiamiane, lrimadawdaroromado si ngimiya.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

dru: ikai ki kakodhane ki Kacalrisiane, alaiyasi ikai ko pasalrio ki badhabadha, ta ngosamadrane si maki dalrodalro loiya, ko marodrange ki cekele wadawlo ki pasalrio si kiapasalrio la taelre irobo, lo irobo kaimakakai makiaseasene, mapelaela podriadringai mapobelebelenge ko kidremedremelini, lo tolrepengenga lapolebe ko bava ko marodrange la kalringolo matakitakili, tako mapalribalribate tokakadroa ko pasalrivane si samadrane. lakoini kakodhane toa sabalay laiya.
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

dru: siadramako kai tairoboaneta kai kameane, anatomane la arakaita ko kakodhane ki sabalay lamakitobitobi mapalribalribate lamaicobongo ka soa kongkoane si Kacalrisiane, la iraroboaneta mapelaela mapobelebelenge ko pasalrivaneta. kai kameane kainako oathoro naokiaseaseneiya, ai lako asidramanenomi tapikidremedreme makanaelre, tamabalibali mapasapokopokoane, lani kaingipelanenga ko matikoroane ko takoalriane, tamakitobitobi ko angidarepane ko amakakidalroane.
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

dru: toapathagilita si tokaroalai kai kameane lakathane, ko lringimia si kailringimia kaika yakai nomiane ka Kacalrisiane si Pingpozoko, ko tangatenganelringa lrika soa kongkoane ko magagemegeme. wathingalako kaikadali kalekete loarakaiyane ko ngodoi karaleale lakathane, ko apasikaiyane ki Kacalrisiane pia sanakamanemane amanilringa ko apatoaladhane, alacegecege ko tengatengane ko samakakidalroane.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

dru: lakai lrisakaiyakokai pelaela nomiane, lri pikaiyako kai Congtongho cegecege ko tamapelaelane ko atopacengecengane ko tapasalrivane. koako lalri sakaiyako ko takatalialaaladhaneli ki Ciokoko kai kameane, si kamani ka magagemegeme ko aongane, lalri taelrenai ki wadaiho ki Kacalrisilrisiane si darepe cegecege ko morikaita, ko taetaleta ka Kacalrisilrisiane si swa kongkoane yarakaita ko mababalrealreanane malalekete, alamapelaela ko apapiane asilolodane ki cekele.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

dru: lai pelaelako podriadrangai, koini tara mapelaelaela ikai Congtongho, ko makociacingalrenga, amani kai cekeleta si Yingcoming ko amalaleketane amababalrealreanane. ko patoakamani, amani kai Pingpo zoko, swadratane, Kacalrisilrisiyane, itaraka nimapalrailraingane ka kidremedreme ki mapapangale. kikai raroboane, ikamani ko mapelaela torathodane ko morikaikaita akolikolita ka kinaocekelane ka Yingcoming makanaelre.
english: I want to stress that this commission places the greatest importance on equality between the country and the indigenous peoples. The election of tribal representatives, including for the Pingpu ethnic group, will take as basis the consensus of peoples and tribes. This commission will serve as a mechanism for collective decision-making by indigenous peoples, and will ensure that the voices of tribe members find true expression.

dru: ko dromanane, konako lrikitobiyako ki Singcenging ko akelretane ko vai ko atakaigiyane ko lri marasikai padromolro ki holrice ki Kacalrisilrisiyane. lo irobo kai wiingkai, ko takarathodane mapalrailraingi ka kadalranane, kai Siho, lri ikai ki sabebelengenga ka takaigiyane, si kithathengete ko mamoamoa ka aongane. paelreelre kikai kyasilape ko tapakelane ngolringao ka lrikisi, padromolro ko angisasingkaiyane ki kacalrisilrisiyane, maramaramao asidi ko sacekecekelane, ko apacongolane ki akibolrowane ki kakodhane, akilakebane pangokai ki akakecengane ki kinaomasane, akilibakane katheme ko amoesadhane ki yadratane ka sakacekeleta.
english: In addition, I will request that our Executive Yuan convene regularly the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law Promotion Committee, and use the Yuan's authority to coordinate and handle matters related to any consensus reached by the above-mentioned commission. These matters include the following: to retrieve historical memories, to promote indigenous self-government, to seek fair economic development, to ensure continuation of culture and education, to safeguard indigenous health, and to protect the rights of urban indigenous peoples, etc.

dru: kai holrice kai asasane si sidromanane ka kakodhane ki Kacalrisiyane, makalra ko kai mamamoa kai masasoadalepe, lai tara cegecegako ko takivagavagane ko kakodhane ki Yingcoming. alalri topelata darepe ko kakodhane ko lrika asodalepane, si mamamoa ki kakodhane ki Kacalrisiane, lanikai mapapongopongo maolrodro kikai sarakaikaiyaneta kai holrice, lani kabekelane ko pangelracane ko apelane torathodane.
english: Where modern laws and indigenous traditional cultures are at odds, we will set up an Indigenous Legal Service Center with a high degree of cultural sensitivity, to reduce through institutional design the growing clashes between indigenous customs and modern laws.

dru: itarapasoalako tokocingalre kitobi ko kiaparaisi ko aongane, tara pasoala demele ko ngwakai ki Kacalrisiane ko aongane, kai Kacalrisiane lo ngoalai ki kakodhane, la kai ki dremedreme ko atoracevane malalangadhane, lamoa ki sakoakadaenganelini toalai ko nadroma, lo alopo si kipoalra la kitopasalrivane si kisaibange. lakamani lokabibilrili kikai ngoalai ki nitopasalrivane ko kakodhane singi kadroma, ta irobo makanaelre lamapelaela si tobavane ko kakodhane.
english: I will ask the relevant agencies to immediately pull together cases in which indigenous community members have been indicted or sentenced for hunting, where the hunting was done in accordance with traditional customs, on traditional lands, and for non-transactional needs, and where the animals hunted were not protected by conservation laws. For such cases we will deliberate solutions.

dru: lai kitobiako ko amani ko piaonganane, ngwalai kai ki obolo ki dingki, ko totacilricilriane pikai Langi toalai sa lripathagili pakelanga kai, lri pelaela ko tangilribatane kotangimiamiane. sakai tolrepengeana demele ko apangimiane kai ki obolo ki dingki, lai tara pasoalanata osakene ki Yamizoko, labai ko sapangibilriane ko takoalrianelini.
english: I will also direct relevant agencies to present an investigative report on the decision-making process of nuclear waste storage on Orchid Island. Before finding a permanent solution for the nuclear waste, we will provide the Yami tribe appropriate compensation.

dru: kai asasane, ngwalai ko taosakenaneta ki Pingpozoko, ko tangipapalrainganelini, tangithathingalanelini, ko tangipapolringavanelini, amaniako ko tengatenganeiya, loka bangate ka dramare si matolrolo ka vai, kaika apalribatane koini, lai mapelaela ko amamamoane ko kakodhane, lani sara arakai ko tacekecekelane, takaomaomasanelini.
english: At the same time, under the principle of respecting the Pingpu ethnic group's self- identity, and recognizing their identity, we will examine relevant laws before September 30 of this year, so that Pingpu ethnic group identity will receive the rights and status it deserves.

dru: kai caili kai asaane, loka mangeale si vaeva ka dramare si vaeva ko vai, ipathagilinganai agisi kai kadaengane, lalri pelaelanai ko kadaengane ki Yingcoming, ko tangimiamiane, ko sarakaiyane mapelaela ki cekele, la arakaikainganai ko kakodhane. lo kabibilrili, ko morikaikaita, ko aingikakadrengane ki Yingcoming iyasidramadrama itarangimiya. koini makociacingalrenga ka morikaikaingata. ka sarakaiyane ki Yingcoming tokakodhane, sarakaiyane ki Yingcoming tokakodhane ki kadaengane si laveke, sarakaiyane ki Yingcoming tokakodhane ki vagalini, patoelre koini, lai satedrenai poa kavai Lripoing, lai drele si mapelaela pangilribate si pangimiya.
english: On November 1 of this year, we will begin to delineate and announce indigenous traditional territories and lands. The system of tribal public corporation is already in place. In the future, the ideals of indigenous self-government will be realized step by step. We will step up the pace and submit for legislative deliberation three laws of great importance to indigenous peoples: the Indigenous Peoples Self-Government Law, the Indigenous Peoples Land and Sea Areas Law, and the Indigenous Languages Development Law.

dru: kai kameane lo makamolringedele, lalri pairobonai ki swa kacalrisilrisiane ki swa kongkoane makanaelre. lakakalra ko amapelaelane. lo kabibilrili, ki caicaili ki valro ka dramare si moa saka vaeva ka vai, kai swa Singcengying, ipelaela ko tapakelanengalini kaongo ki patharokai ki tapacasane ko tangilribatane ki kakodhane ki Yingcoming, ko pangyamiya ko tangilribatane ki Yingcoming ko kakodhanelini, ko wacegecege tokaroalai ko angikakadrengane angisasingkaiyane ki Yingcoming, lakikai tai tolroane, amani ko makociacingalrenga ko akaongane ki swa kongkoane si pangimiya.
english: Later this afternoon, we will convene a national indigenous peoples administrative meeting. In that meeting, the government will elaborate on the policies. On every August 1 to come, the Executive Yuan will report to the indigenous peoples our progress on restoring historical justice and transitional justice. To implement the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law, to serve indigenous historical justice, and to lay the foundation for indigenous self- government - these are the three major goals for the government's policy towards indigenous peoples.

dru: kiatobiako nomiane ka yakaikai, ka yacocobongo ki tingse si wanglo makanaelre ka talragilragili ka Yingcoming, kamania ka wamaca ka peaelaelaela. kiatobiako nomiane kamania ka wakadrenge, kainako lri arakai ko pacase kipokiame nomiane. kiatobiako nomiane ka kinaocekelane arakaia ko pokonomi tokecenge nakoane, bolro nakoane, lani pangimia ko tapokaonane takiketeketane kai swa Siho, lani katengatengane topela ko tangilribataneta ko pasalrivane.
english: To all of our indigenous friends here and watching on TV and online: I invite you to stand witness. I invite you not to endorse, but to oversee. Please keep pressure on the government and right its course where necessary, so that it will realize its commitments and right historical wrongs.

english: I want to thank all of our indigenous friends. You remind everyone in this country that there is irreplaceable value in the land we tread on and the traditions we inherit. This value deserves dignity.

english: In the future, we will push for policies to ensure that succeeding generations of indigenous tribes and all ethnic peoples in Taiwan never lose their languages and memories, that they are never separated from their cultural traditions, and that never again are they lost in a land of their own.

english: I call upon our entire society to come together and get to know our history, get to know our land, and get to know the cultures of our many ethnic peoples. Let us work towards reconciliation, a shared existence and shared prosperity, and a new future for Taiwan.

english: Sweet potatoes are thirty dollars for a pound.

dru: vo'alriyae ta kaeaea 'evehe aa'o la ta kaeaea tingatingi maihange.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and a pound of sweet potatoes.

dru: vaaho, mahimoholrao omece ingpice, amo dholro ka'iyae pasolria?
english: vaaho, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?
I don't have one either. This is dhipolo's.
Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.
Thank you and thank dhipolo for me.
I want to return these two books.
No problem and what else do you need?
I would like to borrow these three books.
Sure and remember to return them after three days.
You haven't returned me the eraser.
Then, why is my eraser missing?
Did you lend it to vaaho?
I don't know. I will go and ask her.
I will lend you my eraser first.
dhipolo, did vaaho lend you this coat?
No, my mom bought it for me.
vaaho's coat is the same as yours.
His coat is black, so our colors are different.
dhipolo, did you borrow money from vaaho?

dru: iya'e, nao 'ailridhe omiyalraidhe men, la kahimoholrao omece paiso.
english: Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?
I will return to him tomorrow.
Okay, I will tell vaaho for you.

dru: a'ata'atange toha'akine apoto totangetange polra, tikohai to'ahakine kelrece polra, nitopodhaolae.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay and catch bamboo partridges through qjiulang.

dru: kapi'anineana, paolilrao tapapi'ae! alakali kilaaka poolra.
english: No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

dru: la nao 'aelraangimiya'e pato'o ta kadho'a tapapi'ae tokoho.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up these two traps.

dru: iya'e! 'inkoolarli! pi'ali ana lamo dholrongalrao malra alopae lo vilrilaenga.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

dru: ooma 'olrao 'oasangedha'a, moa ta'ekelae malra takilrongo, taoa ooma.
english: The grass in the fields is too tall. Go to the warehouse to take the sickle and let's go to the fields.

dru: omiki vakahe vila'a, mo'adhinga ta'ekelae lamo cengelemo'o.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.
Be careful and don't get hurt. The sickle is very sharp.
My trap is under that tree.
I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.
This is a fish trap which we put beside the river for fishing.

dru: tikinai ana ikaodhiname 'atoka'aka'ange lrongolo vakahe, oahatoha'akinai lakisi lroikikisi.
english: We don't have any fish traps there, so we catch fish with a fishing rod.
I have never used a fishing rod before, would you mind teaching me next time?
Sure! Let's go fishing together next time.
I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.
Your fishing rod is moving. Isn't the fish on the hook? Pull it up!

dru: cevanana, 'aelele tohamoho apange. nao iki ina vilivili lrakisi, moa anaheea pasopalriyae malra 'asiyo.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

dru: poiyae vilivili ka'ange 'ina. nao pasopalrimiya'e vilivili.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

dru: 'akosaaeni tadhi'ae! madhao alrata mene, so'etenga vakahe ka'ange.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.
Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.
Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

dru: mene 'a kingyoobi, lo 'idhanga amo ivalriyo, ta 'anoaelre moa 'ooliliyo!
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!
Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?
Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!
What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

dru: neiciyoobi lo 'idha, amo owanai kiwkai inali.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.
I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

dru: sinsi, o'ange'angiyae vahangeli, nao owana tave'ekae.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?

dru: dhalinga i'adha ta solate, cevanana lamo owa mo'o.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

dru: sinsi, lo giceyoobi amo ivalriyolrao, amo owalrao 'icengele koisange.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.
She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

dru: sinsi, Vaaho o'ange'angidhe colo'olraedha, ivalriyo mene.
english: Teacher, Vaaho has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.
My name is Lavohasi omiiyae, and I'm 10 years old.
What ethnic group are you from?
Are all your family members indigenous?

dru: iya'e, dha'ananaeli idhopelenai tali Drekai 'oponoho ocao.
english: Yes, my whole family is Rukai.

dru: 'aina, Amali 'a tali Drekai 'oponoho ocao, inali 'a Pakisa.
english: No, my father is Rukai, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.
Is that your father? How old is he?

dru: 'aina, ana 'a valriyonai ta kahodhangenga, otahamavalrolonga caili.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.
Is your brother much older than you?
I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

dru: apakacehemo'o, otahaeangalrao idhai la kamatolrolo kongfen.

english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.
He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.
Where is Mooni? She's going to compete in a running competition later.
She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

dru: nao ivavaina moa longai kodhali, lamo oalraimiya'e 'ilape.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

dru: moa 'ilape dhoma ocao, amo oalrao 'ilape sinsi.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

dru: Vaaho mene amo pa'ikalromalromale kai kongokongo malri?
english: Is Vaaho competing in croquet today?
No, he's competing in high jump.

dru: tapakahakahalrae dhona menanae amo pakahakahai ka'o?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?

dru: tapakahakahalrae dhona menanae amo pa'ikalromalromale ka'o?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?
What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.
Will we sell food at the sports day?
Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!
Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

dru: omikikai ka, ta'asana molatadhe, amo 'oilri lo maongonga.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.
He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.
It's Vaaho. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?
I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.
He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.
She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

dru: omonomi ka omikikai ka dha'ane, omiki ooma, 'odha'adhalridhe miki dha'ane.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.
I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.
It's so good to see you.
Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

dru: kani ii'aasadha kikaava'i, lanai 'ineyaelre kone aha'a omiyalrao.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.
No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.
Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

dru: 'ina tahokoko ta'asanalrao colo, omeca 'oilri ohamaca kone.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.
Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

dru: nimokoani ta iki gako? amo loingimita.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

dru: ta oa ta'asahovohovoe mataadhiadhi'i, amo 'ikipingilrao kaocaae molraae.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

dru: valriyonai tapangale lo pongepangeni pa'apaalra. lo pongepangengai mava'imayae 'ilape!
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

dru: lamo 'adha'adhao paokela lo kala vengelralrae, mo'adhaili tohamoho!
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Then come during our Harvest Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!
May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.
Why not teach in the city?
Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

dru: olriho'o mo'o dhohepe, aangai ta pato'oto'imiya'e?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

dru: omoli 'avai ta pato'oto'iyae. omoli 'avai olriho'onga ta iki nai valriyo dhohepe.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.
How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

dru: Ta dhahepe 'a bongkanai, nao pacongolo omiyalrao bongka.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.
You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

dru: makapilikai, makapitoloni menanae molekate. ocolokonamao pi'amadhalae dha'akecae vcenge, mani dhalrese poa pa'ivo alrehenge vongo ciciyo, lamani poamao pa'ano palongo.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

dru: 'ina omiki tavangolo la kahidhange, lredhekeli pooler 'ina!
english: I have chili and pigeon pea, both grown by myself!
I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?
It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?
No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

dru: La pii'ana! nao alra matahea taecelrange kipingi.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.
I want this knife and this pot.

dru: poelrelre 'a madho'a kodholo paiso, aangaali ta 'inipapi'a, amo to'ahakimo'o mo'adhaili.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

dru: noa pato'o ivokoli ladha kaava'i longai, aika'o kamo dhoolro tomelre'e?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?

dru: la pii'ana! nao po'alrolrodhimiya'e toeaea kodholo la kaeneme idhai.
english: All right! It's cheap for you, 1600yuan.

dru: imiya oma cengele! olangalangai kipingi la tolropongo.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

dru: kipingi ta kaeaea matolro idhai la kamalrimale paiso, ta katolro kipingi maeaea kodholo paiso.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

dru: amo patahealrao longai, vo'alriyae ta kavaoa'e.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

dru: aika'o polringaao, nao langai omiyalrao valitoho va'oho la potavangolae alopae.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and meat with chili peppers.

dru: poelrengine longai va'oho, omikina ahingihingaye ping, amo langaika'o?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

dru: kanikoaadha! vo'alriyae pakaea vocongo, lo vilrilaenga lamo kavaa'ingalrao longai va'oho.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

dru: ya'e, nao pasopalriya'e potavisie, 'ina 'a mamalrimale paiso.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

dru: mwadringadringai nomi makanaelre. kai vaiyana ai 'athingale ko nomiya kai akanea ikakwata mawriva ka sin Taromaka.
english: Hello everyone. Today, I am going to teach you how to say the Tarumake language for food.
Do you understand what the teacher says?

dru: sinsi, nako wathingale. kalalekete so angi'elra mawriva?
english: I don't understand. Can you repeat it again?
I can't hear you, can you speak louder?

dru: la ccela kikai! ta angi'elana wasi'i.
english: Look here, please! Repeat after me.
Read it again. Please speak louder.
I forgot to bring my pen.
I forgot to bring my eraser.

dru: kisalrowa ki tabere so kwadra yakai ki thili so.
english: Please borrow erasers from your classmates.

dru: akela ta kikai, kai kicakwane ta mwanga ta macecelenga lo kelanga ki takicakowakowane ta
english: Class dismissed, see you next week.
I am the son of Solaging, and my name is 'Aleme.

dru: kiya bolro wako ki Tinebenga, siya 'Otonga. kai nagane li
english: I am a student in Tinebenga, my name is 'Okoringa.

dru: siya nea nagane ki tama so?
ko nagane ki tama li siya 'Alem.
kwani ka taka li ka sawalay, siya 'Odrane.
english: He is my brother, his name is Tanebake.

dru: eene, siya Kako kai nagane ini.
kwani ka agi ki tinali siya Sele'e.
kwani ka alili, siya Molisi nagane ini.
english: She is my friend and her name is Molisi.

dru: mangeale si drosa kai cayli ini.
'iyanga kai cayli ki tama so kaiyasa?
malimalrenga cayli ki tama li kaiyasa.

english: How many brothers and sisters do you have?

dru: yakai ka tadrosa ka takali ka ababay, tangea ka agili ka sawalay.
english: I have two brothers and sisters and one younger brother and sister.

dru: yakai ka taka so ka sawalay?

english: How many people are in your family?
There are four of us in our family.

dru: kwani ka tamali ka agi ki tamali.
ko tama so ka taka ki tina so manema kai lravai ini?
english: What does your uncle do for a living?

dru: yakai ka lravai ki taka so ka ababay?
english: Does your sister have a job?

dru: eene, soTaromaka ko ka Ngodra Drekai.
ko sakacekele so miya ka kacalrisiya?

english: Yes, but she is a Puyuma.

dru: eene, mabelreng nai makanaelre ka wacekecekele.
english: Yes, we are all very tall.

dru: takesikesinga ko agi so ka ababay?
english: Does your sister go to school?
Do your siblings speak the language?
Yes, they speak the ethnic language.
I have three brothers and sisters.

dru: ma'aelre so ki tama so si tina so ikaikai?
english: Do you live with your parents?

dru: eene, ma'aelrea ko ki tamali si tinali ikaikai.
english: Yes, I live with my mom and dad.

dru: waki'aelre so ki tomo so si kaingo so?
english: Do you live with your grandparents?

dru: ini, kadrwa ko ki'aelre ki kolini.
english: No, I didn't live with them.

dru: ma'aelrelrea ko ki tamali, tinali si takali ka sawalay.
english: I live with my father, mother and brother.

dru: ai mobaliyo so mo cekele lroiga?
english: When are you going back to the tribe?

dru: kai taisadrasadra'a ki kaladraidraya tara mobaliyowa ko.
english: I will go back in the summer.
The sun is coming out, it's very hot.
Is it going to be cold outside?
It's cold, so wear more clothes.

dru: kaika makecelre kaika drangdrang kaiyasa, matharirir si kasolra'ele
english: It's neither cold nor hot today, very comfortable.

dru: kadrowa ka emeeme sobelebeleng, walrawng kai tariyaw.
english: There were no clouds in the sky; the stars came out.

dru: mawgawnga, si vaivaivaynga, lrawnga kai balrilawlaw.
english: The rain has just stopped, the sun has come out, the rainbow is coming out.

dru: miyakakwa kai vaiyana talikai ki mosowa?
english: What's the weather like where you are?
We're going to have a big storm here.

dru: mathariri kai vaiyana talikai ki mosowa?

english: Very well, out of the big sun.
I have to go to school.

dru: makecelre kai vaiyana, la tokalra'a si ki'ing.
english: The weather is very cold, so wear more clothes.

dru: ai tarwadraw odale lrwasa, ki karimorimoro iloko sa soko.
english: It's going to rain heavily, you have to remember to bring an umbrella.
There was thunder just now, and it's supposed to rain later.
It just rained, and now it's stopped.

dru: tamiya sa waodale, ni madiretheng kai kaelrea.
english: It seems to have rained and the road is wet.

dru: wa odaodale? aso kadiretheng asawle kai kinawmasane so?
english: Is it raining? Why are you all wet?

dru: wa odaodale latadre, kai nako wailoko sa soko.
english: It's raining outside, so I didn't bring an umbrella.

dru: madraw kai sasevera, angiyacaeme ki awlro li.
english: The wind is blowing so hard that my head hurts.

dru: madraw kai vay, mabithengele kai awlro li takovaiya neli.
english: The sun is so big, it makes me dizzy.
I forgot to bring my pen.
I forgot to bring my chopsticks.

dru: miya neko kadro iloko, 'ila ta mwa langai.
english: I don't have one either, let's go buy one.
Let's go buy a pen, shall we?

dru: eene, ai tako langai yako na samosakisakidra.
english: Well, I still have to buy erasers.

dru: 'ila ta langai sa rokodro sa akanea?
english: Let's go get breakfast, shall we?
No, I've already eaten at home.
I forgot to steam my lunchbox.
I forgot to bring my lunchbox.

dru: ta maelelre kwane ina cabo neli.
english: Then let's eat my lunch box together!

dru: ai kane so samanema lo tokodralidraliya?
english: What are you having for lunch?

dru: ai kanea ko ki tokodraliya ki tatakesikesiya.
english: I want a nutritious school lunch.

dru: wa'iloka ko sa cabo, ta tadrosa tokodrali.
english: I've brought a lunchbox today, let's eat together at noon!

dru: 'ila ta mwa malimali ki rangciyo eene?
english: Let's go play basketball, shall we?

dru: 'ila ta mwa malimali ki yakiyo eene?
ini, ai takesi yako ceele sa 'acase.

english: Please help me with the broom.
Okay, here's a broomstick for you.
Can you help me with the cloth?
I'm sweeping the floor and you asked Kacaw to carry it for you. *[Kacaw] Please change the name to men of all races.
The floor is dirty, go clean it.
Okay, I'll go get the cloth.
That window is very dirty, go clean it.
Wait a minute, I'm not done sweeping here yet.
I'm going to see my teacher.

dru: lo maka takesinga ai toma neso?
english: What do you do after school?

dru: ai to'alra ko ki talragili mwa senay.
english: I'm going to sing with my friends.

dru: lo maka takesinga ai tomatoma ko laso?

english: Is Lisin at home, please? *[Lisin] Please change the name to an ethnic woman.
She's at home, please come in.
She's not here, what can I do for you?

dru: nawmo, amani yako ka Tavarai, moleba.
english: Grandpa, I'm Panay, please open the door. *[Panay] Please change the name to an ethnic woman.

dru: Solaging, Lavaoso zako, wakela ko sila'e mosowa.
english: Kacaw, I'm Mayaw, I've come to play with you. *[Kacaw][Mayaw] Please change the names of the women of each tribe.

dru: eene, mabarengere ko mosawa. niyama takalaelang.
english: Yeah! I miss you so much. Come on, let's chat!
Please sit down and have some tea.

dru: eene, lo celeta kai akanekanea ka madro matiyadalame.
madonga kai waga ki tinali ka kwaobo, niyma kwane.
english: Mom has cooked dinner, come and eat!
Okay, I'll go wash my hands.

dru: 'alaynga kwane si ongolo, maela neso sa bazabaza.
english: Try to eat and drink as much as possible, you're not an outsider.
I ate a lot, I'm full.

dru: ai davacengana ko, naw kelanga ceele mosowa.
english: I'm leaving, I'll see you next time.

dru: eene, lo ocogo so niyamanga niyana kivaevang.
english: Okay, come to my house sometime.

dru: mwadringadringai nomi makanaelre, ai iloka ko nomiya mo cekele ki'elaelra ki tarwarodranga.
english: Hello everyone, today I'm taking you to the tribe to interview the elders.

dru: eene, ai sin Taromaka nai kikawriva ki tarwarodrang.
english: Okay! We're going to say Ngudradrekay to the seniors.

dru: naomo, wa kela nai ceele mosowa.
english: Grandpa, we've come to see you.

dru: ya! wa thingale nomi so Taromaka, matharirir aramoro.
english: You speak Tarumake! That's great! *Please change the language to your native language.

dru: mwadringadringai nomi makanaelre, ai iloka ko nomiya mwa tawbecenga twatoma.
english: Hello everyone, today I will take you to work in the millet field.

dru: niyama tilribi makanaelre, waolringaw ta iloko na satomatomana.
english: Come and line up, remember to bring your tools.

dru: eene, sinsi, wa iloko nai ina sarokorokodro.
english: Yes, sir, we've got our tools.
Not yet, it's still far away.
You go get the bird catcher.
Okay, I'll go and catch the birds.

dru: mwadringadringai nomi makanaelre, ai yowa ta tala'ola'owa dra la golagolay kaivaiyana.
english: Hello everyone, we are going to the zoo today.

dru: eene mathariri, ai ikakwa ta mowa.
english: Awesome! How are we going to get there?

dru: niyama kikai tilribi, ai langaynga ta sa kipo.
english: Everyone line up, we are ready to buy tickets.

dru: kai cocobonga ka lazazame, kai lrikodranga ka laolawlay, angikamaniya siyavava.
english: There are birds in the front and snakes in the back.

dru: kadro kitoma, mwa ceele dra azazame.
english: It doesn't matter, then you go and watch the birds.

dru: lo lribatenga ki eea ka toki, wakela ta irobo kikai.
english: We'll be back in an hour.

dru: manema ka wa ceele so kaivaiyana?
wa ceela ko makalra ka olawlay, si makalra ka azazame.
english: I saw a lot of snakes and a lot of birds.
Hurry up, we have to go.

dru: adrawai li, mabalrebalre kai dra'ale li.
english: Wait for me, my feet are tired.

dru: takalra kai omase yakai kikai lwangolangoy.
english: There are a lot of people swimming here.

dru: madraw si mwadringi kwani acilay kawai, ta ikai kikai langolangoy.
english: The water is deep there, so we just swim here.

dru: ango kai so sa manema kela?
english: What kind of car did you take?

dru: ango kai yako ki baase kela.

english: How do you go to church?

dru: ai obeleng nakowa ko tama li.
ko laso ango kai sa manema mwa tatakesikesiya?
english: How does he usually go to school?

dru: ko laso wa ango kai cie'ing mwa tatakesikesiya.
english: He took the subway to school.

dru: ko kaingo so wa mobeleng sa manema mwa langai ki lacenge?
english: How does your grandmother go to the grocery store?
She went to the grocery store on a motorcycle.
How are you going to get to Orchid Island?

dru: ai angokai ko ki sodang mo Bocolo.
english: I want to take a boat to Lanyu.

dru: ko talragi so la ikakwa mo Bocolo?
english: How did he get to Orchid Island?

dru: wa mobeleng ki hikoki mo Bocolo.
english: He took a plane to Orchid Island.

dru: ango kai sa manema mo Takaw ko talragi so?
english: What bus did he take to Kaohsiung?

dru: ango kai ki kawti mo Takaw.
english: He took the THSR to Kaohsiung.

dru: kai laso ango kai ki kisiya mo Balrangaw?
english: Did he take a train to Taitung?

dru: eene, ango kai ki kisiya mo Balrangaw
english: Yes, he took a train to Taitung.

dru: ko talragi so ango kai ki kisiya mo Balrangaw?
english: Did he take a train to Taitung?

dru: ini, wa mobeleng ki hikoki mo Balrangaw.

dru: lo molatadreta tisiyaba la dadavaceta lima bonkange wakelangata.
english: It only takes five minutes after you walk out of the station.
I would like to visit you.
I am out today. How about another day?

dru: wacogoso loza? naw mwako 'olidraw mwswa lo makatokodrali.
english: Then, are you available tomorrow? I'll visit you tomorrow afternoon.

dru: ahoa miniya, kialalavalavako mwswa ikai naiyana.
english: Sure, I will wait for you at home.

dru: na kaleketako roko'ing? asanga nawako athoro ki 'acase.
english: Would you mind if I do the voice recording? I would like to keep a record.
Would you mind if I do the video recording?

dru: ini,malisabolako kadro mathariri, kwadra lriba miya kadro liethele, ini ki roko'ingi.
english: No, I am plain and the warehouse hasn't been tidied up yet.

dru: lo miya iniya na sasingi katha.
english: Then I will just take photos.

dru: maelanenga so anialralrainginga kielaela ko moswa.
english: Thank you for accepting the interview.

dru: kadro kiyatoma, ai elaela so sa manema?
english: You are welcome. What would you like to know?

dru: sa yacengecenge so manema ka atomananeso?
english: What do you do when you are young?

dru: kodra tolavalavazaneli ka kengesase, wadanonongako kaiyasa.
english: I was a police officer but I am retired now.
Then, are you working at the moment?
Do your kids live in the tribe too?
No, my kids are all living in the city.
Then, do you live by yourself?

dru: wala'o ako taw'ong si azazame,miya ka wacekecekeleli.
english: I also keep a dog and a bird. They are my family.

dru: miya wala'o ako ngiyaw,yakai lo doboco to'a'ala kadro kase'elre.
english: I have a cat too. I won't get bored with the company of my pet.

dru: ai kielaelako moswa idra sana twalisiya ki alro'o.
english: I would like to ask you about the taboos of hunting.

dru: wathingalako ka bekela,lamani ai tobalrako moswa sanaka thingaleli.
english: I don't know much about that, but I will tell you everything I know.

dru: yakai sa manema ka lisi ki salro'a idra sarakaikaiya nomi alro'o?
english: Do you have any taboos about hunting weapons?

dru: kwadra salro'a nai ka sarakaikaiya alro'a kadroy aniswasola'e ki lrabaybay.
english: Our hunting weapons are untouchable to women.
Then, can women go hunting together?
No, women cannot go hunting either.

dru: Tanobake, kadrowanga bava naiyana, lwalangaia bava.
english: Kacaw, our home is out of rice wine, please go and buy some.

dru: yakaiyana sadalrila ikai kwbaw, asi langai!
english: There is still one bottle left in the kitchen, so there is no need to buy one!

dru: kadro ahoa sa dalrila, mwa na angivalre lwangai akoadrosa.
english: One bottle is not enough for me, go and buy two more back.
I am looking for rice wine. Do you have any rice wine?
Yes! How many bottles do you need?

dru: ai langazako drosa ka dalrili bava si langaiyana sa awtiyana ka agai.
english: I want two bottles and a pack of rice.

dru: ikai niya agai, ai langaiyana so sa manema?
english: Here is the rice, what else do you need?

dru: ai lwangaiyana ako batoko, yakai nomi?
english: I want some eggs too, do you have some?
I want to buy some clothes.
What kind of clothes do you like?

dru: ai langazako ki'ingi ka edrekai hasere.
english: I want to buy the clothes with short sleeves.
We have white and blue ones too.
Please give me the clothes in blue.

dru: Tanobake amwa so ino kwasa? mwaongdo so?
english: kacaw, where have you been just now? Did you go exercising?

dru: ini, amwa ko alribolo ki kaingoli langai sa laceng.
english: No, I went grocery shopping for my grandma.

dru: iya! wacogo so lomaong? na karedede takane aga.
english: No wonder! Are you available at night? Would you like to have a meal with me?
No, I want to buy some clothes.
Then, I will go with you.
Hello, how much is this bunch of vegetables?

dru: sabetebete ka laceng ka maosalre ka 'aiso.
english: The vegetables are $20 for a bunch.
How much are these sweet potatoes?

dru: matolrolo ka 'aiso ka sa tingiting ka borasi.
english: Sweet potatoes are thirty dollars for a pound.

dru: na bwayiyaili drosa betebete ka laceng si sa tingiting ka borasi.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and a pound of sweet potatoes.

dru: Kelesai, marimorako iloko 'inpici, akisalro so nakowa?
english: kacaw, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?

dru: miyako kadro iloko, yaki Soliyape kaivai.
english: I don't have one either. This is Soliyape's.

dru: na kalekete so akisalro nakowa adalro? akase sawlako mosowa.
english: Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.
Thank you and thank Panay for me.
I want to return these two books.
No problem and what else do you need?

dru: ai akisalroyana ako kai tolro ka 'acase.
english: I would like to borrow these three books.
Sure and remember to return them after three days.

dru: kadrowa so na sawliyana nakowa idra samosakisakidra.
english: You haven't returned me the eraser.
Then, why is my eraser missing?
Did you lend it to kacaw?

dru: nako thingale, na mwako kielaela iniya.
english: I don't know. I will go and ask her.
I will lend you my eraser first.

dru: Soliyape, kaivai sabelebelenga ki'ingi akisalro mosowa ki Kelesai?
english: panay, did kacaw lend you this coat?

dru: ini, kaivai ka langai ko tinali kibay nakowa.
english: No, my mom bought it for me.

dru: kodra sabelebelenga ki'ingi ki Kelesai mararamaw yasono.
english: kacaw's coat is the same as yours.

dru: kodra sabelebelenga ki'ingi ini ka iceceleng, makaela kolraw naiya.
english: His coat is black, so our colors are different.

dru: Soliyape, wakisalro so ki Kelesai sa 'aiso?
english: panay, did you borrow money from kacaw?

dru: eene, asanga naw sawlako kaivaiyana, marimorako kai iloko 'aiso.
english: Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?
I will return to him tomorrow.

dru: eene, na 'osakaelako mosowa mariva ki Kelesai.
english: Okay, I will tell kacaw for you.

dru: ai arakai nai taene wala toliki, ai arakai nai thelrece wala tikorai, lomiyainiya ka 'atengatenga.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay and catch bamboo partridges through qjiulang.

dru: sika mikay, amoliyako! lamani nako maka'amala ki kaang.
english: No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

dru: lobibilrili naw bolro mosowa ikakwa dware'e kikai tadrosa ka tokolro.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up these two traps.

dru: eene, kathariri miniya, lobibilrili lai anako swalro'o.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

dru: mathangela kai obolo kikai cacane, mwala so kilrong ikai liba niya, naw mwa nai cacane.
english: The grass in the fields is too tall. Go to the warehouse to take the sickle and let's go to the fields.

dru: ikai niya thilri ki adare, lo mwdaane liba 'adringi ai ceele so akainiya.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.

dru: kilalibaka mala, kai kadola. magarange kai kilrong.
english: Be careful and don't get hurt. The sickle is very sharp.

dru: dwakale so ino yaso no tokolo.
akai niya tokololi yakai daedae ki angato.
english: My trap is under that tree.
I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.

dru: kaivai ka soronom, arakaiya nai dakale drakeralre tokaang.
english: This is a fish trap which we put beside the river for fishing.

dru: kadrowa soronom naiya, arakai nai salrakoykoyla tokaang.
english: We don't have any fish traps there, so we catch fish with a fishing rod.

dru: nako arakaiyana salrakoykoyla lrakoyli, na bolrowaili lrakoyli bibilrili eene?
english: I have never used a fishing rod before, would you mind teaching me next time?
Sure! Let's go fishing together next time.

dru: lobibilrili naw bolro ako mosowa dare'e soronom.
english: I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.

dru: wavelevele lrakoyli yaso, yakai kaang kialrakoyli? kirarokodra bilribilri ki kaang.
english: Your fishing rod is moving. Isn't the fish on the hook? Pull it up!

dru: idrengera, avelevele akilingaw kai sodang, yakai yako kikai bilribirli salrakoykoyla, mwa so na kawai alibolrolraili mala na aray si kela nakowa.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

dru: mwa bilribilra kaang twalraidra akela nakowa kikai. na osakaele ko mosowa birlibirli.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

dru: matiyakiyaragai! asiyataleke aramoro kaivaiyana, syaetenga karedrare.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.

dru: ila ta sara mobaliyo akiso'ili sakacekeleta.
english: Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.
Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

dru: sici lima kai vaiyana, taisadra loza, ilata karedede kivaevang!
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!
Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

dru: sinci tolro loza, loza makatokodrali tawa malimali!
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!
What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

dru: niciyo loza, konako si tinali ai mwkiywkai nai.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.
I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.
Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?
It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

dru: sinsi, mabithen gelra ko, lo makatokodrali ai cinciya ko.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

dru: sinsi, lo elanga sinci eea ai cinciya ko, iywako kibo.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.
She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

dru: sinsi, Cegaw kiangeange ki lrolrongo, cinciya kai vaiyana.
english: Teacher, Cegaw has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

dru: siya Riono ako, mangeale nganako kai caylili.
english: My name is Riono, and I'm 10 years old.
What ethnic group are you from?
Are all your family members indigenous?

dru: eene, kacalisiya nai cekecekele ka Drekai.
english: Yes, my whole family is Rukai.

dru: ini, Drekai ko tamali, airange ko tinali.
english: No, my father is Rukai, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

dru: kwani ka tamaso? iyanga kai caylini?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

dru: kwani ka tamaso? iyanga ka caylini?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

dru: maela, omarodrang kwani cekelenai, mavalrolonga caylini.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

dru: iyanga ka cayli ki takaso ka sawalay?
takali mangeale si valro ka caylini.
takaso madradraw mwswa sa makalra ka cayli?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

dru: madadavace nai sa lima ka cayli.
konako ka iday si maso'atele ka bakisiyw.
maolaingata kai macecele, mabelengnga so tamiya?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

dru: eene, konako yakai ka iday si matolrolo ka bakisiyw.
eene, kai yasa konako matolrolo ka tintingi.

english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.

dru: kwani yakai talangolangoza, lowasa ai ma'akwakwa langolangoi.
english: He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

dru: Moni yakai ino. yakaino ko Moni? kwani loasa ai makarakara lrabwale.
english: Where is Moni? She's going to compete in a running competition later.

dru: kwani yakai tairoboroboa ka daane, nawmwa dawolo inia.
english: She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

dru: naw aswala loangai atokodraliya, lowasanenga iywako silae mwswa.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

dru: koso sila'a sadroma, iywako sila'e ki singsi.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

dru: Cegaw kai vaiyana ai makarakaraso ki ceiciyo?
english: Is Cegaw competing in croquet today?

dru: ini, kwani ai makarakara ki takatobi.
english: No, he's competing in high jump.
Will you compete in the sports day?

dru: lo ondokai dra vaiyana kota ai tomaneta?
english: What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.

dru: lo ongdokai ai thakathakaita ki akanekanea?
english: Will we sell food at the sports day?

dru: amalraso ki mwsaka eea, atenganeso angicaeme!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!
Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

dru: kadrwa, kaingo tawmwalatadre dwavace, loamawngo ka aikela modaane.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

dru: yakai ko nawmo belenge ki taetale, mwabelenga sila'e.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

dru: amai Cegaweso, mawlainga kaita macecele mwswa, mwadringadringai so?
english: It's Cegaweso. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?

dru: mwadringadringai zako! kelako silae mwswa tamasososo.
english: I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

dru: tamali yakai kobaw toairo'a, nawa dowaolo.
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.

dru: Laikimi amwa tatarokoka owalra ki tarokoko.
english: She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

dru: tomonomi kadrwa ikai daane, yakai cacane, konomi ikaiya daane kilalava dra kaingangai.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.

dru: mawlainga kaita macecele, madrawngaso si kabeleng.
english: I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.

dru: celako mwswa sa kela mati kiaragaizako
english: It's so good to see you.

dru: kaivaika baaili mwswa ka angodrale, awanga pinsiyang.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

dru: mawlainga kadrwa kela, nawdawlo makanaelre karedede kwane ki aga.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

dru: anisa kaw'ongo, aongolaili sa 'ociya sikatha, tamwa kadaana kasososo.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.
Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

dru: kaivai tarokoko tawcinoloa, iloka si angilralralranga kwane.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

dru: konako si koso tamakaketekete loza lo makatokodrali eene?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

dru: ikaita tatakesikesiya eene? ai kisasinta si roko'ong.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

dru: tawa alrakowa mathaithariri, siyako kaki'inga mwa.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

dru: cekelenai kai saletale lo obengelay mathariri aramoro, lo kala obengelai koso niyamanga sila'e nakowa!
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

dru: wadraw akela ki kalariyariga, abilrilinga aramoro!
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Then come during our Harvest Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

dru: kielaela mwswa aso sali mobaliyo cekecekele?
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.
Why not teach in the city?

dru: amanisa mabarengere ako cekelelinai, anatoma kalalekete angibilri ki cekele.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

dru: malrigiliso tinono. aneaka wabolro athingale mwswa.
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

dru: amani ko kaingoli, kwani malrilrigilinga tinono ikai ki cekelenai ka omase.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.

dru: ikakwasi asokisana kicakwa ki tinono amiya?
english: How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

dru: kakoza nai kai tinono, kiadremedremako dra kalalekete congolo ki kakoza.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

dru: kaivai tanobava ki beceng mathariri ongolota.

english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

dru: ini, aka 'itolo ahoanga. doray aswalata olralidring akado, la aibo ki 'ikake si ciboko la wangacinga.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

dru: kikai yakai ka tavangolo si rakiyo, amaniako ka owadroli lre'eng.
english: I have chili and lokiy, both grown by myself!

dru: okasa ka drosa ka iday si malimale ka aiso.
madalamako kikai ki'ing, iya ka aiso?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?

dru: kaivai ka lima ka iday ka aiso.

english: It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?
No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

dru: eene! bazaili sa eea icecelreng na ki'ing.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.
I want this knife and this pot.

dru: okasa ka drosa ka kodrolo ka aiso, kaivai ka aralimako dware'e, kalalekete arakai kaolai amiyako.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

dru: naw elaela ovaga ki talragili kela loangay, kalalekete toadolro sabekela?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?

dru: niyama ceele! ki'ing talro'ono yakai thakathakai.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

dru: eea ka ki'ing tolro ka iday si malimale ka aiso, loatolro ka kodrolo ka aiso.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

dru: larangazako saeea ahoanga, bwazaili dra bawva.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

dru: mwadringadringaiso, kisana langai ako ki binereberese si base ki lomomo.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and mountain Pepper Soup.

dru: mwalangainga le'eng. yakaiyana ka tinpera ki tana, ai langai so?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

dru: eene! bwazaili sa eea, lo elanga nakelanga lwangi ki binereberese.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

dru: eene! nacwabo arakai ki soroido, malimale ka aiso.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

dru: margi momo. sékorodro ma mitai nga.
margi momo. singsi ka noboroboro ma mwa ko akanata pang Teldrekane spasobékénidria.
english: Hello everyone. Today I am going to teach you how to say food in Teldreka.

dru: orgo moso bicilringi ko spasobkéni ki singsi?
english: Do you understand what the teacher says?

dru: singsi, ilrigo kwa, doroma kola kovale mosobakala?
english: I don't understand. Can you repeat it again?
I can't hear you, can you speak louder?

dru: cngla kené! ngélava kwa isisipi kovale.
english: Look here, please! Repeat after me.
Read it again. Please speak louder.
I forgot to bring my pencil.
I forgot to bring my eraser.
Please borrow erasers from your classmates.

dru: tathémanga kené asolotata. skakolanenga géciobi tapcacngle.
english: Class dismissed, see you next week.

dru: Valedra koa Momo do, Kanao kɨkɨ.
english: I am Mumu's son, my name is Kanau.

dru: seto dra Momo do, Kanao kɨkɨ.
english: I'm a student at Mumu, my name is Kanau.

dru: kini ka kakinema sovlé. Aras mania.
english: He's my brother, his name is Arase.

dru: Ipolo kini. kini ka gilidri abéya ninema.

english: She is my friend, her name is Milrinu.

dru: cacevélé ka pidra cvélé ni kini?
cacevélé ka makemangsale kodro sa cvélé kini.
cacevélé ka pidra cvélé ni mami mwa?
cacevélé ka mrémele cvelé ni mamin nema.

english: How many brothers and sisters do you have?

dru: ikéng kwa sesa kaka sovlé sesa kaka abéya, drosa na kaka, sesa gili sovlé, sesa gili abéya.
english: I have two brothers and sisters and one younger brother and sister.
How many people are in your family?
There are four of us in our family.

dru: iko mamimwa ka aci ko sidepani kini?
english: What does your uncle do for a living?
Does your sister have a job?
Yes, we are all very tall.
Does your sister go to school?
Do your siblings speak the language?
Yes, they speak the ethnic language.
How many brothers and sisters do you have?
I have three brothers and sisters.

dru: teresɨ moso ki mama si nina iké danɨ?
english: Do you live with your parents?

dru: iyo, terese kɨkɨ ki mama si nina iké dane.
english: Yes, I live with my mom and dad.

dru: teresɨ moso ki momo si kakoringo iké danɨ?
english: Do you live with your grandparents?
No, I didn't live with them.

dru: aci ko steresɨ so iké danɨ?
terese kɨkɨ ki mama, nina si kaka sovlé iké dane.
english: I live with my father, mother and brother.
Our home is in Mau Forest.

dru: ika tékadra da mo ko yiene?

english: When are you going back to the tribe?

dru: akina tébabarvia na klapane ka sivilri kɨkɨ moa.
english: I will go back in the summer.

dru: orosonga avé, sakora marpa na viene.
english: The sun is coming out, it's very hot.
Is it going to be cold outside?
It's cold, so wear more clothes.

dru: iktatlɨkɨ si ikɨrapa sesa, sakora margi.
english: It's neither cold nor hot today, very comfortable.

dru: tɨbɨlɨnga tédra na korongo, moboelɨnga cacɨngalɨ.
english: There were no clouds in the sky; the stars came out.
The rain has just stopped, the sun has come out, the rainbow is coming out.
What's the weather like where you are?
We're going to have a big storm here.
Very well, out of the big sun.
I have to go to school.

dru: sakora matilɨke na viɨne, skopia pkadro.
english: The weather is very cold, so wear more clothes.

dru: adrara nodalema sokora, ngolringava emɨcɨ na thkebe.
english: It's going to rain heavily, you have to remember to bring an umbrella.
There was thunder just now, and it's supposed to rain later.
It just rained, and now it's stopped.
It seems to have rained and the road is wet.
Is it raining? Why are you all wet?

dru: odale blate, si imɨcɨ kɨkɨ na thkebe.
english: It's raining outside, so I didn't bring an umbrella.

dru: tradro na bsɨsɨ, absɨbsani ka otrɨtrɨ oroli.
english: The wind is blowing so hard that my head hurts.

dru: sakora na ocɨngtre. acengɨrvani ka maboso ko oroli.
