She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

dru: singsi, ki legeageay ka wa'ange'ange na tolo'owanidra, sesane ka nosikaami.
english: Teacher, legeageay has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

dru: akake ka legeageay.thabilane, watamangesale na cavilili.
english: My name is Noami Kulas, and I'm 10 years old.
What ethnic group are you from?

dru: kake ka valavalakini kowa na lrekay zoko.

english: Are all your family members indigenous?
Yes, my whole family is Rukai.

dru: 'aini, ki tatavi nakowa ka lrekay zoko, ki titini nakowa ka pakisa.
english: No, my father is Rukai, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

dru: kodro ka tatavi nyani mosowa? watapyaninga na cavilini?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

dru: kidro ka tatavi nyani mosowa? watapyaninga na cavilini?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

dru: 'aini, kini ka odranginame tacekecekelane, watamavaolonga na cavilini.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

dru: ki kaka mosowa ka watapyaninga na cavilini?
ki kaka namiya ka watamangesale sika vao na casvilini.
ki kaka mosowa cavilini ka tawmomo nyani mosowa?
english: Is your brother much older than you?
I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?
I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.
He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

dru: ki 'ongawlo ka 'iyakayni? no tiday amiya pa'akawmawmale.
english: Where is 'ongawlo? She's going to compete in a running competition later.
She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

dru: si kowala lwangay na kidrali, adralala si koso silape mosowa.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

dru: mwa silape na cwao, nowa mikake silape singsiyane.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

dru: ki tangoco sesane ka no pa'akawmawmale myani na coycyo?
english: Is tangoco competing in croquet today?
No, he's competing in high jump.

dru: dryane 'ongdokai ka no kisa'apa myaso pa'akawmawmale?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?

dru: no kisa'ap mikake pa'akawmawmale na coycyo.
dryane 'ongdokay ka va'iyane ka manini paythyanita?
english: What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.

dru: dyane ko no 'ongdokayanita ka manin ko langayanita na kane?
english: Will we sell food at the sports day?

dru: amalra koso na mwaskasea, tyakadringay maki'ecenge!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!
Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

dru: i'ikai, ta'obalatela, no 'ama'awbo amiya laso sivi.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.
He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

dru: esi legeageay aa, 'iyakikaynga nili cengela mosowa. ipoingao nyaso?
english: It's legeageay. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?

dru: magyagi'i kake! 'awkay kake namo pababaka mya.
english: I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.
He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.
She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

dru: ki tawmo mwane ka i'ikay da'ane, 'iyakay tawmoma, 'ikaya da'ane 'owadra'adrao.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.
I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.
It's so good to see you.

dru: kikai pangodrale ka ba'aili mwane, pawa pingsyange.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

dru: 'iyakikaynga nimiaokai. kowa kwakwao tatakaese kwane na do'o.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

dru: 'ayni adrikaykoco, ko 'ongolo na 'ocya ka mwaebate, ta'ikay ta'avavane mababaka.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.

dru: masityakadringay mama namiya twaomana, no'abenga mikake.
english: Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

dru: kikai taokoko ka 'iyacocolonga, wameca 'abe lapadalamanee kwane.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

dru: kake si koso nosi'i'a noviva'anenga ka tapacacengeleni?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

dru: no'ikay mikita gako macaceengeli magi'i nyani? nopaytha mikita na 'iga.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.
Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

dru: tacekecekelaniname ko ngapale hahana ka nopwangepangini ka magi'i. no pwangepangininga ka 'awkaya silape nakowa.
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

dru: no'adra'adrao mikita nomwaninga na tadangedangane, sawkwa 'aikodrangane.
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Then come during our Harvest Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

dru: ko kiboboi mosowa mani ka 'aelayso 'awkay 'ikai tacekecekelane sikace.
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.
Why not teach in the city?

dru: nikwani ka kyadredreme kake na tacekecekelanili, samanga lapabii kak tacekecekelane mikake.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

dru: waigo'o nyaso di'ici, nanini ko paigo'o mosowa.
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

dru: amani ki takaongo nakowa, amani kini ko waigoygo'onga d'ici tacekecekelaniname.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.

dru: manini ka kokica'owane na wadi'ici myaso.
english: How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

dru: 'ana wadi'ici ka amani ko bengka name, pakidredreme kake nipacongolo bengkaname mya.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

dru: kikai becenge kabavane ka magi'i no'ongolimade.
sawkwa koso maygigili, kikai notibavaimade ka no'ikaykai myamade?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

dru: 'ai, nopakapitolo amina va'iyane. amlra kimade ko kapagane si pagai pawgogo, lapo'ibo kimade na aegenge swamo, lapawa kimade cabake loi.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

dru: nakowa nakay ka 'iyakay na tavangolo si tavangane, maesale 'angidadoko'ili!
english: I have chili and lokiy, both grown by myself!

dru: drodrosa ko lwangayso ka pyani na payso?
madalame kake nakai kokopingi, pyani na payso?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?
It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?

dru: doiya, nopolelebili ka no songsolri mikake.
english: No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

dru: siminysne! si ko pii na maycenge na kopingi.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

dru: noalra mikake na bakale si palongo.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

dru: 'angico'olo ka 2000 na payso, kikai ka 'angipaythili, tyakalringay nodoo mikoso 'ikikikay syakai.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

dru: ko syokai na la'osyli/lalili nilangai, doo myaso polelebe 'angititi'ici?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?
Alright! I'll give you a 20% discount.

dru: ngwalra cengecengela! walangalangai kiname na kopingi si tawpongo.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

dru: kokiboboi mosowa kikai kokopingi ka piyani na payso.
sesesane na kopingi ka 350 na payso, na too ka 1000 na payso.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

dru: nolangay mikake 'angisesa, si bwa'a nakowa na ba'owane.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

dru: ipoingaw nyaso, 'apilangay kake na kapagane na bowao si makao na botolo.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and braised pork with maqaw pepper.

dru: bobwao ka maepengenga lwangay. 'iyakayla nakowa na dena na tingpolra, nolangay myaso.
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

dru: e'e! tisesana nakowa bwa'ay, nobilane ka no'awkayla mikake lwangay.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

dru: e'e! ko pasopai mosowa syakay na thobongo pothobongo, na aminaky ka 50 na payso.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

dru: mani 'inikookono o'i tamatama moa, kapavaahahenga salodhihi o'i titina. aangai toimite pi'a 'ina

english: I arrived at school at seven today.

dru: osolatenga, sinsi modha'ane taikikiyae solate, caha'enai vanidho mani iya 'ina, "idhi'iya! sokova!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

dru: osolatengani, singisi mani paoto'oto'iname 'aa'ia'ipi kaocae vaha.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Rukai language of numbers.
We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.
I have learned many Rukai languages.

dru: pamenanaelrao moa gako, pamenanaelrao 'ica'oca'o kaocae vaha, amo 'aovaovahalrao pasiyalalalra inali.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Rukai language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

dru: omikiyae ta kaeaea taka 'aolai, alracedha 'a taotao, mene caili otahamangele la kaeaea caili.
english: I have a brother, his name is taotao, he is 11 years old.

dru: ta'aelrenai miki ta kaeaea gako solasolate.
english: We study in the same school.
Both my brother and I like to sing.

dru: madhalamelrao longolangoi, lo taivalrivalriyae, cekelaenai dha'ananae moa longolangoi.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

dru: madhalamelrao tova'oae la'ivoko, odholromao ta'aelre omale la longolangoi.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.

dru: dha'ananaenai omiki ta katolro pa'atakatakali 'aolai la 'avai.
english: There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

dru: ta'aelrelrao amali, inali, takali 'aolai la takali 'avai.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.
My father is tall and he is a policeman.
My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.
My father speaks the Rukai language with us at home.
We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.
My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.
I went out with my mother today.

dru: alidhaa'e tevelengae 'ako kadhalremedheme, kikakeecelre la kikalraapa'a, ve'eve'e maateleke.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

dru: omikinai 'olra'olraae kone minpao, koli'iname votolro'onai, tohamoho ka malraveve.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.
I asked my mother why the sky is red.

dru: inali mani pato'iyae, maelretamo kaava'inga ovelre.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

dru: maongo tevelengae ikaodho ka keme'e, mokavolenga tahiyo.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.
On the way home, I made a wish with the stars
I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

dru: gakoli omiki vila'ani dha'anenai, pamenanaelrao dhoadhaace moa gako, la dhadhaacelrao 'oilri.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

dru: gakonai ka matoalraikai, madhaokai ka vanidho, malrihilriho'onai.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

dru: kapa aolrolainga 'asahovo miki ta'ondhoondhoe', ta'aelre 'osahiyo malri, ta'aelre 'avaevaehe.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

dru: sinsinai la ta'aelriname 'osahiyo, gakonai 'a toalrai dha'ananae.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.
We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

dru: omiki ta 'odho'odho ta'avangae, iiki ta 'oa'oape vekenelre.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

dru: o'oa'oapeenai kapa taviiviivila'enga gakonai, ma'apasopalrapalranai, gakonai lo menanae masinakete kikakodholro.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.
Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.
We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

dru: omoli 'aolai acengeledhiyae, mani pakaniyae siikoa, pa'ongoliyae 'ociya.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

dru: omoli 'aolai lredhekeni siikoa malimeme, mataadhi'i kone.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.
I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.
At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

dru: omoli 'avai oaha'a todhao ta kataadhi'i kodhali, omiki ka'ange, omiki tahokoko, omiki tahamonahe la hoholrongo.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

dru: apakakanenganai kodhali, mani oanai talatengae ketekete aa'o.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

dru: omoli 'avai madhao alrani maihange, tai la nigi voa'iyae, omecamiyae 'oilri.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

dru: dhaacengalrao iyalrailidhe, amo kaava'ingalrainome cengele iyalrailidhe.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

dru: mene sinsi oaviliname moa talapolapoe ta odhiodhipi, omikinai talapingae malolodho longai kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

dru: aodha'anenganai talapolapoe ta odhiodhipi, sinsi mani pato'iname, "talicovongae 'a aalrame, alrikodhae 'a 'olra'a, cekelaenai 'inikakamai cengecengele."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back
I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

dru: ocengelelrao ta kadhao aalrame, makinikie 'angato larahalre 'inpalapalai, mani cengelelrao ko'o ta iki 'angato takaloangae 'apece.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

dru: talapolapoe ta odhiodhipi omiki zoo, rihi, lrikolao, 'onaina ocengelenakali ti'a 'ina ta odhiodhipi, mene ocengelengalrao akosaeniyae mapala'a 'iidheme mahavehavehe.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.
I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.
Next time I will come with my parents.

dru: 'ina taivalriyae menanae, ilraae la takali 'avai omoanai taito cengele 'adhini amali.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.
We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

dru: aoekelanganai taito, 'adhini amali 'ongting haiya maava'i moa tiisaba 'icivonginame.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

dru: tiisaba ma'adhailikai ka dha'aneni amali 'adhini, 'ongting haiya padhalro'omao la okela.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

dru: amali 'adhini dha'aneni taka'adhidhalie omiki ta katoaalrainga talapolapoe 'olrao, 'anoaelrenai 'anosakale moa talapolapoe 'olrao.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

dru: ikinai talapolaopoe 'olrao, amali 'adhini aviliname moa pakane kii'i la 'anolrihinai.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

dru: maongonae, mani kahedhelenai moa sechi kone ko'ovo.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

dru: sechi madhao sangepahe, 'atolohonai ano 'otobai moa dhona.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

dru: na'oilringanai aiyanai, kapa ko'opangidhe 'otobai, mani lrongainai 'ano sangepahe lroahai.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.
Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

dru: akalrolaili dha'anenai omiki 'oponoho, asolasolatengali mani, 'aelanai moa hiito, mahadhaolonga miki lrevake siikace.
english: When we were young, our family lived in 'oponoho. After I started school, we moved to Pingtung and have been living in the city ever since.

dru: aoangali dhaigako, mani pilrilrao ta kaeaea kaocae bongka 'i solate, ta'asalrao lrio'o taiwan kaocae ta tohamoho ma'akaelela tai'aeni bongka.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

dru: to'atolohaeli, 'ina mene caili kalalrapa'ae taivalrivalriyae, ilraae la takali 'aolai kaava'inai movalriyo 'itovolrovolro ta kaahodhange, nai lriho'o toce'elao zokonai bongka iyanai.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

dru: ta kahodhange otahamavalrolonga caili, lalo cengelemaidhe i'ana ta icengecenge make'ecenge ocaodha.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

dru: mani 'itovolrolraidhe kavahadha alriho'ae'o, alriho'aedha macaci'o 'a 'oponoho vaha, la lriiho'o paiwan vaha, bonong vaha la nipong vaha.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in 'oponoho, as well as Paiwan, Bunun and Japanese.

dru: a'itovolrongalidhe ta'asalrao lriho'o, akalrolaidha 'a 'ipato'oto'onga nipong vaha, la lamengaedha 'a tali paiwan ocao, la 'ihakii taikiedha 'asika'olo mani palrihilriho'o tali bongo ocao, to'atolohaedha lriho'o kapa vahanga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Paiwan, and he knows many Bunun at work, so he can speak so many languages.

dru: ona a'itovolronaidhe, dhona ta kahodhange pato'iname ta kadhao 'aamadhalae tapapi'aeni ta alopo.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

dru: topodhaolae ka poelrekanai lriho'o sialalra, oha'eve la to'ahakinai soci lo'ing, dholromao 'oelaanga toce'elao siyalara.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

dru: akalrolaili matilriho'okali ka zokonai bongkani, ilraae kaocaelrao lo miyali 'akoka'iniyae.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

dru: alriho'ongali kinatodhaoenga, mani 'inyaiyangalrao 'ina 'oponoholra ocao, 'a maiconganae tai'aeni iyalrao, 'initatoelaelangalrao.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a 'oponoho is unique and something to be proud of.
My younger brother is going home this evening.

dru: ilraae la omoli 'avai omoanai secange longai tahokoko, oaha'anai taadhi'inga ko'ovo dhomate ladhakane 'adhili 'aolai miya.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

dru: olrivatenai talangalangalrae aa'o, talangalangalrae aa'o madhao ta lredhelredhe 'iya'aoen a aa'o.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.
We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

dru: vila'a ta langalangai madho laopange mani iya 'ina, "pangodhaleli la mimilriki malimeme. kai longalra!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

dru: olrivatenai ta langalangai tahokoko, laopange mani iya 'ina, "kanani langalra'o? mene tahokoko matoalrai la ka'ima'a, ta kaeaea matolro idhai."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

dru: omoli 'avai makocingai mani iya, 'itovolro laopange kai 'akotomelre'a iya.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

dru: la laopange mani iya 'ina tomelre'engalrao, dhoolrongakai ka 'oalralra.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

dru: ta ivila'a laopange iya 'ina, longalra ka'angeli, ka'angeli 'a matoalrai la kamelree'e.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

dru: vilrilaenga olangainai tahokoko laangainai ka'ange, 'oilringanai oha'a paso'ete cokoi 'adhamai.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

dru: 'adhili 'aolai mani lingilingi miya 'ina, hitai apakacokai kidholro ka paovalriyo, oonai lo niciyoobinga lamo dholro maava'i.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

dru: omoli 'avai mani iya 'ina, oaha'angamita todhao, imiya ta cekelae 'inyaelre kone!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

dru: mani alraalraalranai palrapalra la la'ivi'ivokonai, 'iniyaelrenai kone ta tohamoho madhao ko'ovo.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

dru: omiki elreelreli vaaho omiidhe, kama ahakahimoho omece 'ahakikidha.
english: I have a classmate named Vaaho, he often forgets to bring things.

dru: lo solatedha, mani 'ipasolriya elreelreedha inpice, 'acocaocao la tapikikiyae solate.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.
Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

dru: oha'eve la omiki takatakolraedha ta to'inilrao, lo 'ipasolriyadha ka olriho'okadha ka 'oilri.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.
In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

dru: iiki ta kaeaea menane, cekelaenai molatadhe 'oliliyo.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

dru: tavalrevalre'anae, vaaho 'api otavilavila'ae, la kahimoho omece oisengce.
english: On the way, Kacaw wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

dru: mani 'ipasolriya elreelreedha oisengce, la cekelaenai miidhe 'ina, oameecekali.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

dru: vaaho pokoali iya tovi. mani kasekelre miya 'ina, kani cekelaaenomi, kipasolriiyae oisengce!
english: Vaaho burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

dru: elreelreedha mani pato'idhe, olriho'oka'o ka 'iniyamece, lo pasolriyanaimiya'e kilriho'ongamo'o ka 'oilri!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

dru: 'idhanaenga aoadha gako, vaaho 'anolake'enga moa gako, vaaho 'ipasolriyaedha elreelredha mani poelrenga 'oilri voa'i elreelreedha.
english: The next day at school, Vaaho arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

dru: vaaho mani liicinganomi iya elreelreedha, matalaki mani iya 'ina lo vilrilaenga amo 'iniyamecengalrao 'ahakikili, icongonganomi elreelreeli 'amadhalae dholronomi pasolriyae 'ahakiki.
english: Vaaho apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.
My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

dru: ona akalrolainli, amali la 'adhini 'aolai lo maongo molatadhe, 'ikoange la 'iya'alodho.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

dru: malehengai, mani ovalriyo omece alralini alopae.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

dru: dhomanae omiki vavoi, iiki lraa, omikii lo mikidha. tikohai.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

dru: taesa miki valriyo tai'adha'adhae apa'aavinga alopae, mani apa'avi voa'i cinekelae.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

dru: taesalrao makaalai amali, nao 'anopapalra olopo miya.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

dru: mani iyae amali 'ina onailo maolohonga'o amo avililraimiya'e.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

dru: valriyonai a'olalai olrihoo'o tokoho alopae, olriho'o to'akelrecae la totangetange tokoho.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

dru: amali malrihili to'akelrecae tokoho, amali omiya 'ina, 'ina 'a 'atokoho tikohai, amo pa'iniyacehaemita cengele alopae dhakaseni, lo tokohomao opikimao 'oloni alopae.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

dru: 'ihakilrao nao padhalro'o dholro 'anoaelriline atamatama olopo miya, pamenanaelrao loalala to'atokohae, ki'asaino tokoholi mani dholronga paotokoho alopae.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

dru: amali acengelengai mani iyae 'ina lo vilrilaenga amo 'anomakaelaemo'o malrihili oloalopo.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

dru: 'inanga maolohongalrao, mani angelengalrao vo'oli la lrailili, 'ano papalrangalro amali olopo.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

dru: aovalriyonganai mani apa'avinai alranai alopae voa'i ocao povocongo.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

dru: amali mani iya 'ina, amo icongongai miyamita loomo pa'apelengaimite, mani alramita todhao alopae.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.
I was late for school this morning.
When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

dru: lo solatenai 'a, ta'aelrelrao elreelreli cengele solate.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.
During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.
The teacher told me, "Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!"
My good friend's name is 'Esai, and he is also an Rukai child.
We study together in the 'Oponoho tribe.

dru: osilalalranai takaarodhange lo lomoamolailidha, la kalrihilinai 'ako'Oponohae.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the 'Oponohae proficiently.

dru: maka'anahalrelrao la kavotolro'o, 'Esai 'a maka'analeve la karilai.
english: I am tall and overweight, while 'Esai is short and thin.
'Esai is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.
Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

dru: omiki mavilivilivili, zocio, lrolrame, 'odholri la pana.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.
When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.
But I stood up and continued running forward.

dru: aoangali taolropengae 'a cekelaiae maraveravere ana ocao.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

dru: topodhaolae ka omalrakali ka 'akaea la maraveraverelrao, alakai pa'alropengelrao ma'ikalromale.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

dru: o'idha 'a 'anodhadho'alrao amali moa cengele pa'atakani amali.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.
He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.
He fell off the roof while repairing it.

dru: oamece aamae votolo la saviki voa'idhe pa'atakani amali.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

dru: ma'olionai pa'atakani amali iki taikikiaedha, madhao pato'oeniae lamolai.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

dru: naodhaace aiali 'a toelaeliae pa'atakani amali, "maolohongamo'o, kinakasavaraenga." omi.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

dru: mani ialrao 'ina, "amake, lo mataadhi'ingai okoko'o 'a maava'imainame dha'anenai 'olilio."
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

dru: 2022 cail, ma'olilionga siihe pataliki nibongsio oara'isolate kaocae alrace mia.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

dru: 'itovolrolraine Lakadhaalae Taotao dhona tao'adhailinga takaamai 'iva'ai siihe oara'isolate kaocae alrace.
english: I interviewed Lakadhaalae Taotao, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.
We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

dru: tapa'oliaenai 'a mani pato'iae toloraeni alracedha, mani aviliae palriho'o dha'ananaedha la valriodha.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

dru: mani 'itovolrolraine, "kani kake'eecenge'o naopatapavalrisae 'ina alrace, matakolrakai tapapia'eni 'amadhalae?" mia.
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

dru: mani iiae 'ina "to'arakita Ciokoko asolataeni 'a odholrokai ka matopodhaolae palriho'o ocao, amoiiki tamopoalracidhe "la savare" mia. amookavole takataka'oma'omalrae."
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \La Xian Sheng

dru: mani ia omidhe ana Lakadhaale Taotao, "'ina kaocae asolataeni 'a aanai takatopodhaolae alrace. 'ina alraceli 'a movavalre 'ina'i zokonai, ta'itoloraenai dha'ananae la takaocaeta. 'amalraine lani cekelae 'i ocao 'otomo ta'itoloraeta alrace."
english: Lakadhaale Taotao said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

dru: 'idha 'a 'anopapalralrao oomoe moa talangalangalrae longalangai. oamece oomoe todhao alredheedhekaeni aa'o moa longalangai. mani tokane 'ina akanekanaeta kaocae voa'i ocao.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

dru: cekelae madhalame talangalangalraeni oomoe. madhao ocao talangai 'ama la valangato, la kadhao taoa loalaala kone aha'ani 'adhamai.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the \nBlack Nightshade and Manila Champereia, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

dru: mataadhi'i kone aha'ani lrokolrokoco la talivee'ae, la dhona alopae poa 'i karidhange to'asolro'ae. 'aanoami'ani 'a madhao valravalrae takaava'i, cekelae maava'i talangalangalraenai mahedhele.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and pigeon pea soup. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

dru: lo ohaaha'ani oomoe 'a mani ikilrao vila'a malramalramalra valravalrae, tako'iase, "'inilralredhekenai, ka posavo'okai. maava'ia pakono moa longai."
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

dru: 'ipilikai ka mani poelrenai longalangai. "omikimo'o la mani dholromi'iae pasopalra." mani iiae omoli.
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

dru: 'irakilrao 'ina tako'ica'oca'o mani lriho'ongalrao 'ina kaocae 'alredheedheke la akanekanae 'i lrihilae. omoangalrao 'itokalae 'ina'i talangalangalangai vare'aeni.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

dru: tacengelaeli oomoe 'a madhalame tokaocaocae tokane, 'initatoelaelalrao maraveravere.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

dru: kai vaiyana mo tatakesikesiyako ki 'ito ka toki ki miyalrealre.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

dru: la ai kicakwanganai, sa modaane ko sinsinai ki takibolrobolrowa, ko pangcan kai taberanai la aminiya kawriva "'idiya! songalra!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

dru: la akwadrawnai makanaelre sinsi "mwadringadringaiso amiya kawariva.
sa kicakwakwa nai, ko sinsinai la 'elaela naiya sinTaromakana wasi'i.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Rukai language of numbers.

dru: la to'a'arlanai wasi'i, ko sinsinai la 'elaela naiya 'asenaya ki 'wasi'i.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

dru: makalra kai kicekwaneli si la wathingalenganako sin Taromakana.
english: I have learned many Rukai languages.

dru: watwakesi yako tothadalrane, wakicakwako ki kwacalrilrisiyana tothadalrane, ai 'akilalrako ki tinali.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Rukai language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

dru: siya Gaita ko nagane ki tamali.
siya Dolray ko nagane ki tinali.
yakai ka tangea ka takali ka sawalay, siya Masegesege kai naganeini,tara mangealenga si eea kai cayli ini.
english: I have a brother, his name is Masegesege, he is 11 years old.

dru: yakai nai tayangea ki tatakesikesiya twakesi.
english: We study in the same school.

dru: konako si takali ka sawalay madalame nai senay.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

dru: madalamako langoy,lo taisadrasadraza maelrelre nai ka cekecekele mwa langolangoy.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

dru: madalamako mathingathingale ki bawva ka talragi, la kalekete nai maelrelre senasenay si lwangolwangoy.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

dru: konako si tama, tina, taka ka sawalay si taka ka ababay maelrelre nai.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

dru: ko tamali ka mabelreng, kensase ko tamali.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

dru: marilay ko tinali, ko tinali ka 'ising.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

dru: lo ikai daane ko tamali wa soTaromakana makawrivariva naiya.
english: My father speaks the Rukai language with us at home.

dru: lo taisadrasadra ki kaladraidraza wa mobaliyo nai cekele.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

dru: konako si latakali maelrelre nai mwa walra ina takolariyase.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.

dru: kai vaiya maelrelre ko ki tinali mwa kivaevang.
english: I went out with my mother today.

dru: kai vaiyana masalese kai sobelebeleng, kadro makecelre kadro drangedrang, mangangerece kai sasevere.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

dru: yakai nai ki tasiobola twakainene si kanekane mingpaw, kai vai 'asaelre ki kinaomasa nai masolra'ele 'aramoro.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

dru: la ki'elaelako ki tinali, asi madirerele kai sobelebeleng?
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

dru: ko tinali kawriva laiya, ai kela kai masasevesevere.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

dru: kai amaong kadrowa ka emeeme sobelebeleng, mwtalrivaivainga tariyaw.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

dru: ikai kaelrea mobaliyo, sidramadramako ki tariyaw
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

dru: anatoma la nikai kela kai masasevesevere, angielra kivaevang kidremedremeli.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

dru: kai tatakesikesiyanai yakai thili ki naiyana, tothadalranako dadavace mwa tatakesikesiya, miya dadavace mobaliyo.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

dru: kai tatakesikesiyanai kadro madraw, kadrowa ka takakalra ka takesikesi, mathingathingale nai makanaelre.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

dru: konai ka lavavalake mokasa nai ikai ki dradralraza, la maelrelrenai angimalimali, si makawrivariva si masososo.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

dru: ko lasinsi miya kiaelre naiya kivaevaevang, takamiya nai ka wacekecekele.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

dru: tothadalranai swaswa'e, nikabola ki takibolrobolrowa nai amiyanai makanaelre.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

dru: yakai ka tabere mwa mosakisakidri lribang, si kwadra ladroma ka tabere mwa swaswaswa'e daeda'e.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

dru: wa swaswa'e nai asaelre ki laro'osonga ki tatakesikesiyanai, wa karathodo nai si mavalavala ina atomana, la kadelese tothadalrane kai tatakesikesiyanai.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

dru: koza, mobaliyo nai ki cekelenai mwa 'olridraw ki tomoli.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

dru: mawlainga kanai maceceele ki tomoli, mabarengerako ki tomoli.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

dru: sa ceele nakowa ki tomoli, ko tomoli 'asadalro nakwa 'oakane seika si 'wcia.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

dru: malrimeme kai seika ki 'odroli ki tomoli, atengatenga mwadringai aramoro.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

dru: miya madalamako kai 'wcia ki tomoli, miya ka mwadringai.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

dru: lo kodralridralriya, maelrelrako si kaingoli twaga kodralri.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

dru: ko kaingoli twaga kodralri taleke, yakai sa kaang, tarokoko, taramonage si dingding.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

dru: sa maka tokodralri, amwanai lacaceng ki laceng.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

dru: ko kaingoli mala madromolro ka birasi, tay si rakiyo bay nakowa, amala iloko mobaliyo.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

dru: si aokiyovagai lriniya, si mawriva ko bilrilanenga naw kela 'olridraw lriniya.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

dru: kai vaiyana ko sinsi iloko naiya mwa tala'ola'owa ki lagolagolay, yalangai nai sa kipo la tilribi nai ikai ki sawlatadra.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

dru: sa modaanenga nai, ko sinsi laelraela naiya, "kai cocobonga ka lazazame, kai lrikodranga ka laolawlay, angikamaniyata ceele si siyavava."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

dru: mwakolodrako ki olawlay, amanisa nako kiyaomaw mwa ceele laolawlay.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

dru: waceelako makalra azazame, yabeleng ki angato aniya'ala'alay, si waceelako loo yakai barongolo 'adring ki angato wa'e'ece.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

dru: kai tala'ola'owa ki golagolay yakai ka zoo, baa si lrikolaw, nakowaceelana kai lagolagolay saiyana, kai vaiyana waceelanganako matiyakiraragai kidremedrameli.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

dru: la sasiyasingako makalra ka sasing, ai bwaiyako 'aceele ki marodrawdrang.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

dru: lo abilrilinga ai maelrelreako si marodraodrang anivalre kela.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

dru: kai taisadrasadra nai, tadrosa nai ka takali ka ababay si konako mwlrika'e ki agi ki tamali ikai Balangaw.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

dru: mwbeleng kisiya nai twalai Taipake na kala Balrangaw.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

dru: sa kelanganai Balrangaw, ko agi ki tamali ango sidosiya si kela kisiya kidreseng naiya.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

dru: kadro wadayli kodaana ki gai ki tamali, 'lo angota sidosiya 'adalro wakelata.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

dru: kodaana ki agi ki tamali sa'agiyagisi yakai ka madraw ka tala'ola'owa ki golagolay, ango 'aliliding nai mwa tala'ola'owa ki golagolay.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

dru: ikainai iniya, ko agi ki tamali iloko naiya walomo bo'a'e si mobeleng ki baa.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

dru: sa amaong, maelrelrenai mwa maci kwane sa aga.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

dru: lo ikai maci makalra ka sidosiya, amanisa ango nai 'otobay mwa kawai.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

dru: sa amwadadavace nai, la kidringai 'otobaiyanai ki'akotrakilinga, la mobelengnai baase si davace mobaliyo.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

dru: wa mobaliyonganai kela Taipake kaiyasa, kadro thingale idra kidringainga 'otobay ki agi ki tamali amiyanai kidremedreme.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

dru: sa lrolraina naiya takaikaiya so Taromake, si atwanaw takesiyana, lra mwsali Taicyo, tara ikai maci tacekecekelra.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Taromake. After I started school, we moved to Taichung and have been living in the city ever since.

dru: na kelanga taikake, watakesiako eea ka takesi idra kakoza ki kacelisiya, athingale nakowa makaelraela kakoza ki kacalisiya so Taivang.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

dru: amanisa, taisadrasadraza ki kaladraidraza, konako si takali ka sawalay mwbaliyowa cekeleli kielraelra lramarodrang, anatoma si alrecega yataka cekele kakozaneta.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

dru: tara mavalolronga ka cayli ini kai marodrang, eene loceele takamaiya yacengeceng.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

dru: lamani ko kielraelra idra wathingale taiya ka vagana, kali'ace ini sing Taromakana, miya maligilri swa Songaw, swa Talalibeka, swa Di'ong.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Taromak, as well as Bunun, Pinuyumayan and Japanese.

dru: la kielraelrako kwani na akithingale nakowa, si sa lrolrainga wakicakwa ini vaga ki swa Di'ong, ko sakacekele ini ka swa Songaw, mathingathingale takalra swa Talalibeka ikai tatwlavalavaza ini, amanisa malalekete kawriva makalra ka makaelraelra vagana.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Bunun, and he knows many Pinuyumayan at work, so he can speak so many languages.

dru: lo tamasososo sakibolobolo nai,ko marodrang elraelraelra makalra kwadra sininadroma lrigila ki alro'o.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

dru: eene odrava lo kadrowa makathingale kidremedreme nai, la ni arakaiya nai ki soci rako'ing, lai kalalekete nai kilalra twadriyadringai.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

dru: sa lrolrainganako nako thingale kakoza ki cekeleta, maininoako ki sw kwacalisiya.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

dru: sa wathingale arokakalra, lo kidremedremeli sw Taromakako ka nikalrivala, miya ka anikamiya.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Taromak is unique and something to be proud of.

dru: lo amiyaobo, ai mwbaliyo ko agili ka sawalay.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

dru: konako si kaingoli amwa nai maci langai sa tarokoko, adolro kwaobo ka mwadringai akane ki agili ka sawalay.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

dru: sa lribate nai talacenga, ikai talacenga yakai ka makala ka ngetangeta ka laceng.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

dru: walangai nai sa 'incai, bakway si ningiging.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

dru: kwani tawki ka thilri tiyang ka kilrangai sa madro mawriva matikaikay amiya, "malrimeme kai angodraleli si vinwate obawbala. lwangai'a kobekela!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

dru: la langai nai angodrale si vinwate obawbala.
sa lribate nai kai tiyang ka kilrangai sa botolo, la mawriva tawki matikay, "ai langai sa manema? kaivaiyana madraw si karocolo kai tarokoko, tolro ka idai ka 'aiso ka eea."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

dru: lo miniya ka makocingalre aramoro kidremedreme ki kaingoli, si kielraelra tawki kalekete ma'adolro kobekela.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

dru: la kwani tawki tobale nai amiya ma'adodolronga, kai kalekete 'oda'eda'e 'aiso laiya.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

dru: kodra yathili ka tawki la dawdawdaw, nyama lwangai'a kaangeli, madraw si ma'adolro laiya.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

dru: sabilrilanenga walangai nai tarokoko si kaang mwdaane twaga asiyaete ki too.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.

dru: maolai nai kiya lalavalava si madralemedremenga.
english: After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

dru: la ki'adrelre agili nakowa mawriva matikay, atwanaw kanai isasadra swa sivwtai, naw mwbaliyako lo elra taisadrasadraza.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

dru: ko kaingoli mawriva amiyaikay twaganga ko taleke, mwa dawlo lrakay takane'a!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

dru: la dawdawlo nai ki lraretesa si lratalagi, akela maelele mita akiso'ili kane kwaobo ka taleke.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

dru: yakai yako tangea ka tabereli sya Kecelre, tara karimoro iloko ini lamanema.
english: I have a classmate named Kecelre, he often forgets to bring things.

dru: lo kibolobolo nai, kwani wakisalro latabere idra cingpi, samosakisakidra si ciywming.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

dru: angivale, angi'osale, angitolrolo, akisalro iniya makanaelre.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

dru: amanisa, yakai ka malisi iyaiyaiya ini, tara wakisalro si kai sawli.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

dru: sabilrilanenga kadro kiaomaw makanaelre akisalro iniya.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

dru: yakai sa makavale,kota ka makanaelre maedede mwa kivaevang.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

dru: ikai kaelrelrea yowata, Kecelre ai mwa laang,si karimoro iloko weysengce.
english: On the way, Kecelre wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

dru: la kwani wakisalro weysengce ki latabere, si konai ka makanaelre tobalre iniya amiyaikay, miyaliyako kadrowa iloko laiya.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

dru: la kasasibolo tobitobi Kecelre, si kalisi mawriva amiyaikay,asi kai akisalro weysengce nakowa makanaelre!
english: Kecelre burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

dru: lamani ko latabere elraelra iniya, asiloiya kaso ilokoiyasono, lo akisalro moswa lamanema, kadrwy sawli!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

dru: lo azana, mwlalakese ko Kecelre asabale kelanga baolo, na sawli lamanema idra wakisalro ini ki latabere.
english: The next day at school, Kecelre arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

dru: 'ayy amoliyaili laiya ko Kecelre ki latabere, wathingalenganako laiya si loiganenga ai angiyailokako,si kiyaseaseng ki latabere owakaene akisalro iniya lamanema.
english: Kecelre apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

dru: ko tamali ka tara ana'ana yata ka cekele.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

dru: sa lrolainganako, ko tamali si agiini wadavace lo amaong, wailoko dra labo bakalre si kwang.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

dru: lo lredranga, lai wailoko lini swalro'o mobaliyo.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

dru: yakailo baboy, yakailo ravare, nadroma miyakai sadamatha.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

dru: kolini avalavalanga swalro'o ikai tamwadriadringa ki cekele, akiso'ili sakacekele.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

dru: loiya makavalazako ki tamali, ai to'alra tamali alro'o.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

dru: ko tamali mawriva amiyaikay, lo kadrawnga so naw iloko mosowa.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

dru: ko sawalai ki cekele yakailo arakai tokolro 'aana, wadare'elini thelrece si taene.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

dru: ko tamali ka malrigili dare'e thelrece, si mawriva amiyaikay, kaivai ka sarakaiya wala sadamatha, ai caceela si kilralibaka nai idra taodra'ala ki waodriodri'i, ai drakale nai tokolro ikai talranelriniya.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

dru: alrolrodo kalralekete kirarokodro to'alra ki lratamatama alro'o, tothadalanako kicakwa dare'e tokolro, 'adalo wa'ana tokolroli.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

dru: la ceele ko tamali mawriva nakowa amiyaikay, lobibilrili ai mwelra tino tara ana'ana si malrigili so.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

dru: kaiyasa madrawnganako,waelraiyako kwadra boo si lraylili,to'a'alra tamali alro'o.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

dru: kainganai avalavala si akiso'ili swalro'o ki sakacekele.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

dru: ko tamali elraelra amiyaikay, konai ai kiyaseasengta sa sobolobolo ki lratomoita, la ataromara makala ka swalro'o.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.
I was late for school this morning.

dru: samwako ki tatakesikesiya, la karimorako iloko ina labaceli.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

dru: sa takesikesinai, konako si sataberaneli la mokasanai ceele ki 'acase.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

dru: sa sikingnai, kai sataberaneli la 'akisalro nakowa 'inpici si samosakisakidra.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

dru: ko singsinai la iniya kawriva nakwa, "loelanga molalakesa angidrakale, kai abilribilrilinga!"
english: The teacher told me, "Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!"

dru: ko talragili siya 'Alri, miya lalake ki Ngodradrekai.
english: My good friend's name is Alri, and he is also an Rukai child.

dru: wamaelrelrenai ikai ki cekelenai Taromak twakesikesi.
english: We study together in the Taromak tribe.

dru: tara maelrelrenai kilalalra ki tarwarodrang lo tomaowlawlay, miya malrigilinai sinTaromakakaana.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Rukai proficiently.

dru: mabelrengako si kabitolro, ko 'Alri malebe si karilai.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Alri is short and thin.

dru: ko 'Alri wa'ararakenga, madalamenai makanaelre ki iniya.
english: Alri is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

dru: Kaivaiyana 'ongdokai tatakesikesiya, makarakara makalra ikai tatakesikesiya.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

dru: yakai ka mabilibilibili sakakereng, ti'iti'isi mali, lrabwale, malikasaw si lraylrayli.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

dru: salrabwale ako, moarairay ako, acolro twaerairay sa makalra.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

dru: amanisa angidrakale ako, twsatamiya a'otalicobong lrabwale.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

dru: sa danolako kainganai kai laomase wakiaragai.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

dru: ene kadro ako amalra sa mwsakaeea, amanisa kiaragai ako, asilwiya danolako makarakara.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

dru: koza konako si tamali amwanai lika'e agi tamali ka sawalay.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

dru: madola dra'ale agi ki tamali ka sawalay.
kwani elaela naiya, daane calraviya matrabelrang eea ka barongolo
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

dru: kwani sa 'odringadringi calraviya, twalai calravaya mocili mwdaedae.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

dru: tamali wailoko bwate ki goong si sabiki baai ki agi ki tamali ka sawalay.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

dru: konako si agi ki tamale ka sawaly ikai daane masosososo. Kawni akiso'ili sa makalra maolai
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

dru: sa aikiovagaizako, agi tamali ka sawalay osamalra nakoa mabelengnga, si haro aniomasa miya.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

dru: la kawrivako, "nama ai adravako dra'aleso modringainga, lo ela niyamanga naiyana kivaevang."
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

dru: 2022 ka cayli, sihe dawlo kaigi athorokai lakacalisiya nibongsiyo kalalekete teasikatha kacalisiyana wacase nagane ikai belenge.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

dru: kielaela ako anisikalralenga kisana kecengana malra "teasikatha sinagane kwacalisiyana" yakai cekele ki mwkathabara ka Cegaw.
english: I interviewed Noami Kulas, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

dru: konako si kwani makaketeketenai kikai niciyo mwaliniyana homong.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

dru: ikai tahomongnga. aiya nakoa elaela tatwalaza acoga ki naganeini. tako iloko nakwa athingale cekecekeleini, si cekeleini.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

dru: la kielaela ako asorakedre aela ki nagane, malisi koani sw'ili ta'acasa?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

dru: la kawriva nakwa, lo arakai lrawtiyatiya kadroi kalalekete mwa'ahoa 'elaela acoga ki nagane, kai droma ka omase arakai "Ce syngseng" la asolwkai kimacacava.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him Na Xian Sheng

dru: Cegaw la kawriva, "koacalisiyana wa'acase 'onagane atengatenga ahoa. naganeli ka daihiyo yanai swmanema kacalisiya, yanai ka cekecekele, yanai ka loloda, anatomasi arotakalra kai laretesa malra sawli naganelini."
english: Noami Kulas said, The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

dru: koza konako si kaingo amwanai iciba taikaiya thakathakai, ko kaingo iloko sa makalra 'odrolini laceng mwa, watwairoa moadriadringai kacalisiya akanea baai ki laomase.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

dru: madalame makanaelre taikaiya thakathakai ki kaingo, takalra ka omase walangai ki tavangolo si rasease, takalra ka omase kela 'alavalava againi airo'a.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

dru: twairo'a maongo si tobinereberese moadringai aramoro, lamani niakama bwate ki baboy, tasabaliyana kiakadalame takalra ki bazabaza, kela makanaelre tilibi.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

dru: lowagaga ko kaingo, yakayako thili aiaidi ki bazabaza. yakaiyako thili akwadraw tawtaw, "'odrolinai kaivai laceng kadroa ni'osababo, imiya loangai!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, The vegetables are self-grown

dru: akase mwlangai lamanemanenai lre'eng, ko kaingo amiyaikai, "yakaiso 'osakaelre kikai lakwani"
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, It's all thanks to your help.""

dru: kavai tamasikaikaita, kicakwako matikai ki kacalisiya racave si akanekanea kodra ki ligila, si kiabalra ako tikaiya thakathakai lamanema kiadolro aramoro.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

dru: celeako ki kaingo madralame ki sinikadroma kanekaneta, konako 'acoco'o si maesai kiragai aramoro tamiyaneli.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

dru: Se sa pito toké mi ni nga ka noa ma kɨ ga ko.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

dru: W sla te nag, singsi motane, ciaosɨ so pakbaka, "icikla!so ko bo!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

dru: La pe ta ra dro ke na me psobaka, "Singsi margagimoso."
I solte ne me dria, o boro boro nema singsi sisipi na beké na m ɨ.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Ruaki language of numbers.

dru: Ang pa ra na mɨ singsi na sisipi, so thɨné nga na mɨ sisipi thɨné.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

dru: Madro arigwa li na makacoko nga na beka.
english: I have learned many Ruaki languages.

dru: Makavienenga mwa solte, kbo bolo beké ta, m pso ba ka ma kɨ biciringi nina na.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Ruaki language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

dru: A ki aracɨ li ka Utagɨ.
Ma mi ne ma aracɨ dra ka Adriyo.
Ni ne ma aracɨ dra ka Momoni.
Ikɨ cacɨvélé ka mɨngesɨle cɨvé li.
I ké koa sesa na kaka sovɨlé, aracɨ dra ka Sɨsɨgɨ, cɨvélé dra ka mɨngesɨle kesesanɨ
english: I have a brother, his name is Sɨsɨgɨ, he is 11 years old.

dru: Terese ke na me iké sesa na gako solsolte.
english: We study in the same school.

dru: Kɨkɨ si kakinema sovlé ka madalamɨ namɨ thɨné.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

dru: Madalamɨ kɨ longolongé, I sa se dra ne me ka, a ngo ro boa kename thɨkadane moa longolongé.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

dru: Madalamɨ kɨ merariko na booa lɨsé, nodoro ma kɨneme teresɨ thɨné si longolongé.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.

dru: Da na mɨ ka iké tarima na ico.
english: There are five people in our family.

dru: Da na mɨ iké tatoro na le ma ta ketaka.
english: There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

dru: Kɨkɨ si mama, nina, kaka sovlé, kaka abéya teresɨ kɨ namɨ.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.
My father is tall and he is a policeman.
My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

dru: Iky ni mama dane ka o teldredrekane nema posobaka.
english: My father speaks the Rukai language with us at home.

dru: Isasɨdra name ki boboranemɨ ka abɨrɨ kɨnamɨ sɨviri cɨkɨlɨ.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

dru: kɨkɨ si kaka sovlé kaka abéya amoa namɨ poara tkorpangɨ
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

dru: Sakora kɨkɨ madalamɨ thɨkadang namɨ na ico.
english: I like our family very much.

dru: Sesa nongeresɨ ma kɨ ninema moa bɨrlɨlé.
english: I went out with my mother today.

dru: Lilepɨ ni tɨbɨlɨnga temalesɨsɨkɨ vyénɨ ikatilekɨ si ikɨrapa, mabɨlɨsbɨsɨ.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

dru: Iké namɨ soro déta kwonɨ pan avé odrerapese nɨma, sakora margi.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

dru: Kiboroboro kɨkɨ ninɨma, nakoni matililyenge nga tɨbɨlɨnga.
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

dru: Nina masobaka, amé nokɨné ma na sɨbɨrɨ
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

dru: Ngiyobo tɨbɨlɨnga ka tédra korongo, cacɨngalɨ ka moboolenga.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

dru: Siviri neme daderanɨ, patoloro kɨ cacɨngalɨ peké kɨdredreme li msobaka.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

dru: Sɨmarnga sɨbɨrɨ ikoani, api berɨlɨlé kwa
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

dru: Gako li iké danamɨ pila, odɨvadɨvacɨ kɨ moa gako, la dɨvadɨvacɨ kɨ siviri.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

dru: Ikɨtaradro gako namɨ, ikadro séto, makasi rɨsama kɨnamɨ mɨmrigrigo.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

dru: Iko valɨvalɨke nga iké beladɨ, isarɨbo, mililivi babangɨ, si modradrɨke.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

dru: Gako toména teradro na thekadanɨ, sinsi ka teresɨ nɨma a mililivi.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

dru: Makavénenga tasisyepɨ ma kɨnamɨ, tapitibola cioosɨ sisyepɨ
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

dru: Iké na ico odrisidrisi tanva, si lake na ico osisyepɨ.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

dru: Uroko kenamɨ syepɨ Gako makatɨporoanga, mvalevala depɨ, gako ka makavénenga mobola nga.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

dru: Kosia, ka amoa kɨkɨ cɨkɨlɨ homong mia momona.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.
We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

dru: Cɨngɨlɨning koa momo ka, pakanɨ kwa soika, la ponglo kwa ocia.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

dru: Momo atoka ni soika ka malemɨmɨ, marigi goonɨ madɨ.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

dru: Madɨlamɨ kwa ocia ni momo, margi ngolo madɨ.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

dru: A vévanɨ ni ka, kɨkɨ si kakorongo teresɨ kɨnamɨ tékane kedrali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

dru: Sakora margi tékana ni kɨdrali kakrongo, iké akange, iké tɨroga, iké tɨngɨtɨngɨ, si laké momolɨ ia.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

dru: Mkakanɨ nɨmɨ nga kedrali ka, amoa kɨnamɨ tɨlacɨnga klacɨngɨ.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

dru: Madro arani bɨrathi kakorongo, até si rakio la péng kwa, ngɨmca psiviri mia.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

dru: A moa kɨdria tila nogiyadra takɨdrɨngémo mia msobaka skakolanɨnga nomakɨmoa cɨnglɨ.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

dru: Sesa ka omɨcɨ nɨma singsi mwa tɨbrlelara cɨnglɨ na makagologolé nga, idilipi kɨnamɨ iké sodadana longé kipo
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

dru: Mɨdanɨ neme nga adringi, lapsobaka singsi, "tlocobonga ka maka raramɨ nga, kodrɨnga ka maka sora nga, rikɨmania cɨngcɨnglɨ lia."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

dru: Akorodro kɨ sora, sokéli ikɨdalemɨ cngɨeleɨ maka sora nga.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

dru: Madro acɨngɨngla li raramɨ, iké angato thilithilibi, laké tɨralobo angato adringi siyerekɨ.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

dru: Tɨberlɨlara adringi ka iké cɨgo, rɨgi si rokolo, icɨngcɨngla li tominia na tɨradro makagologolénga ka, sesa cɨnglɨ li nga ka mabɨbɨrɨ kɨkɨ.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

dru: Madro pasiasinga li siasingi, pcɨngɨlɨ ma kɨ mama na si nina na.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

dru: Skakolanga ngeresɨ ma kɨ mama si nina na mokɨné.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

dru: Kɨné tébabarvia, kɨkɨ si kaka abéya amoa namɨ Taito homon mia mama na.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

dru: Saliké namɨ Taihoko kiodo kisia mwa Taito.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

dru: Moi nɨme nga Taito, mama sokɨné nga désiaba ondéng sidosia drɨsngɨ nɨma.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

dru: Da dra mama édadɨlé tésiaba, ondéng ni sidosia ka isipiylɨ so wa nga.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

dru: Mama da dra bila ka iké tɨradro tɨthathada na makagologolénga, angɨrngɨlɨ namɨ avétha dria.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

dru: Iké nɨme tɨthathada dria mama lamɨcɨ nɨma pɨkanɨ iyo si kiodo rɨgi.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

dru: Ko ngiyobo nga, langɨresɨ namɨ mwa lɨdrɨke tɨkiobo.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

dru: Lɨdrɨke madro na sidosia, sokénɨme ngotoby mwa dria.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

dru: Kogia minɨmenga, cɨnglɨ nɨme otoby ka kioba dria, takorongé ngobaso gia.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

dru: Siviri nɨme Taihoko nga, mokonoa nga otoby dra mama.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

dru: A valɨvalɨke nɨme ka iké namɨ sdanɨ Oponoho, sollte nɨme nga ka, sowanga aola Takao, iké lɨdreke sékaco mia.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Oponoho. After I started school, we moved to Kaohsiung and have been living in the city ever since.

dru: Moili solte daikakosé nga, la kboboro poké sesa na kɨcarisia solate, rigo ko Taioan kɨcarisia makacoko nga na margi bonka.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

dru: Sokéni cacɨvélé tébarbarvia ka, kɨkɨ si kaka sovlé so siviri nga namɨ cɨkɨlɨ kboboro marodrɨngɨ, tarigo ko coko ta si bonka ta mia.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

dru: Kɨné marodrangɨ ka mvarlo cevél dra, makasi cnglɨ madɨ armé na thɨbarɨ la na ico.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

dru: Kiboboro kɨdria aci ko arigoaso na bka, orogo Poponganɨ, mathoré psobaké dra, laigo Konadavan bka, Aoba si Sodé na bka.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Oponoho, as well as Kongadavane, Japanese and Vudavudadhane.

dru: Kiboroboro kɨ dria laigo kɨ, avalɨvalɨke dra ka kiboro boro Poponganɨ bka, asiradra ka Konadavan ico, tikadra kamlo ka madro so Aoba ico, sokédra rigo makabaka nga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Oponoho language when he was a child, his wife is an Kongadavane, and he knows many Japanese at work, so he can speak so many languages.

dru: Tika nɨme mabka dria, ki marodrangɨ la porkéké ololopo na sakiké sirigo.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

dru: Ipta pɨdrɨngɨ namɨ piciringi rigo, makasi iké nɨma dénva saké loing mia, doro pɨtapɨdrɨngé ligiri rigo.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

dru: A valɨvalɨke li ka irigo kɨ coko li si bonka li, langirigo kɨkɨ kcarisian kɨ mia ikeela maoromalɨ matɨ.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

dru: Rigo mdɨnga ngédro ka, la rigo madɨ Drekai coko ico mia, sakwa angola, odoro madɨ pkilovo.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Rukai is unique and something to be proud of.

dru: Sesa ngiobo gili sovlé nokɨla ma aɨbɨrɨ nga.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

dru: A mwa namɨ tɨlanlanra longé toroka kakorongo, zonbi mia pɨtaramɨ gili sovlé tlacngɨ tékɨnanɨ kiobo.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

dru: Orbatɨ namɨ tlanngra lɨcenge, madro dria na marigi booala lɨcenge.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

dru: Onglɨngé namɨ konsing lɨcenge, tɨlacɨ si tétho ia.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

dru: Pila olɨngélɨngé na kodamono lawpan lapsobka, malɨmɨmɨ pngodrele li si mɨnedɨ longia ngitkici!
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

dru: La lɨngé nga namɨ pngodrɨle si menedɨ.
La ribatɨ namɨ tlanngɨra botolo, laopan soposobaka "nolɨngara so? toroka ka tradro si lakocoro, sesa ka toro ɨdé."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

dru: Kakorongo ka makcɨngéma, kbobora laopan na dro ma ptimɨrɨ.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

dru: Makasi laopan ka masobka mamɨrɨ nga, idoro ovavara lia.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

dru: Iko pila laopan masobka, nanga longia akangɨ li, akangɨ li ka teradro si la kɨmɨrɨ.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

dru: Iprilanga olɨngé namɨ akangɨ si toroka, siviri tɨdamé sesa cokoé na kɨnɨ.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

dru: La dénva psiviri gili sovlé psobaka, idroro séka mia hétai ma, skanicoobi nga ka doro ma siviri abɨrɨ.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

dru: Kakorongo masobka tésdamɨra li madro, tila ngoroboa mokené koonɨ mia ma!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

dru: Nanga mokɨnia ma namɨ lɨmngmngnɨ tkɨrɨsɨ koonɨ margi na kiobo.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

dru: Iké kwa sesa na dokiosé aracɨ dra ka Sisipo, maimimoro ɨngmcɨ na sakiké.
english: I have a classmate named Sisipu, he often forgets to bring things.

dru: Soltɨ dra dria, kidri la kébébé dokiosé na ingpico, sidrisidrisi si solatɨ ia.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

dru: Kooalɨ, kopsalɨ, kotrolo, rɨsa no ma boi dra ksédemɨ.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

dru: Makasi iké nia na makorathɨ sasiké, mémani nga ksédemɨ sakiké si isvéré.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

dru: Brinɨnga ka rɨsama aonɨ boi dria ksédemɨ nga.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

dru: Iké sesa na viéne, angorobwa namɨ brɨlɨlé mwa bɨlatɨ.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

dru: Dadɨranɨ dria, Sisipo lapioa béncio, makasi maimoro ɨngmcɨ na sasidrisidrisi solatɨ.
english: On the way, Sisipu wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

dru: La kbébé dokiosé sidrisidrisi na solatɨ, makasi rɨsama biri dria msobaka, imecɨ kɨ mia nia.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

dru: Sisipo la dirvanɨ tobi mgaoco msobaka, nakomo rɨsamia aonɨ ksédemɨ kwa sidrisidrisi solatɨ!
english: Sisipu burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

dru: La psobaka nia dokiosé, idoro moso mlémɨcɨ, ksédemɨ ni swa na sakiké, si idoro moso sasɨvéré!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

dru: Misyenɨnga, Sisipo anglaksɨ mokɨné gako, Sisipo la ra sovri nga dria késɨdɨma dra na sakiké boi dokiosé.
english: The next day at school, Sisipu arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

dru: Sisipo la sokobo dokiosé dra, psobaka koyɨnɨnga nongimɨcɨ makɨ sakiké kwa, takdrengé mo mia dokiosé dra drianɨ doro ksédemɨ driana sakiké.
english: Sisipu apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

dru: Maninɨma ka amani cɨkɨlɨ namɨ ololopo na ico.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

dru: Avalɨvalɨke li ka, mama si gili dria mama ka iké na masongo mbalte mélémɨcɨ lɨvasɨ si koongɨ.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

dru: Mɨlerɨ ni nga, la plémɨcɨ nga arani na bɨrɨ pabɨrɨ.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

dru: Iké kdroma na vlisɨne, iké rɨva, iké kdroma na dmathɨ ia.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

dru: Iké sodadanɨ tɨbabarvia pavalvala nga aradra bobé cɨkɨlɨ ico.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

dru: Tésa opongo kɨkɨ mama na, ksapara makɨ mama na mwa olopo mia.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

dru: Mama lapsobaka taradro li nga ka nomɨcɨ ma kwa ngɨresɨ mwa ma.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

dru: Cɨkɨlɨ na sovalé ka orogo saké tokoro na bɨrɨ, largo saké na tɨrɨbɨ si alapi drodralɨ na sakiké tkoro.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

dru: Maminɨma ka orogo pétha tɨrɨbɨ sa tkoro, mama masobka, kɨné saké pora na dmathe, taptapɨdrɨngɨ cɨnglɨ tkapnga dra bɨrɨ, tkoro ka piké ti sanké dra na bɨrɨ dodavce dadɨranɨ.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

dru: Kérké kɨkɨ koibongo mia ngeresɨ patɨmanɨ ico mwa olopo, makavienɨgna kɨkɨ kboboro pétha tɨrɨbɨ, nosipiyla apétha li na tɨrɨbɨ ka doro ma tokoro na bɨrɨ.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

dru: Mama cɨnglɨ dra nga lapsobaka kwa koiyenɨnga nokɨmani ma moso amani na makɨcɨngɨ nga ololopo na ico mia.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

dru: Kené nga tradro nga kɨkɨ, la kɨvécé kɨ pɨna si rɨvél li, ksapara mama na mwa olopo.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

dru: Abɨrɨ nɨme nga tbarbarvia mɨradria bɨrɨ pavlavla boby cɨkɨlɨ name ico masiarara.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

dru: Masobka mama, takdrɨngé ni taia pɨlɨngɨ ta boimitia tkargia, la doro miti mra ngédro makabɨrɨ nga.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

dru: moili gako mierɨ ka isobribrili kɨkɨ.
english: I was late for school this morning.

dru: moili gako ka, maimoro kɨkɨ emɨcɨ kabangɨ.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

dru: solteli ka, angeresɨ kɨkɨ leséli cɨngɨlɨ solate.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

dru: skéngknamɨ ka, pasakéngkoa lséli ingpico si sdrisdrisi.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

dru: lséli ka kokoi, vlakɨ ni drokay zoko kini.
english: My good friend's name is kukui, and he is also an Rukai child.
We study together in the Teldreka tribe.

dru: sitalsɨ kɨnamɨ biciringi maorodrenge toboboro orogo kɨname téldrɨdrɨkane.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Rukai proficiently.

dru: maragre si lakocoro kɨkɨ, kokoi ka tikca si lakerɨlé.
english: I am tall and overweight, while kukui is short and thin.

dru: sakora kcɨngna ki kokoi, rsamania mdalme ico.
english: kukui is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

dru: ongdokai sesa gakko madro ko nopakelani.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

dru: iké na mabablibli tési okdangɨ babngɨ thorobo si opna.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.
When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.
But I stood up and continued running forward.

dru: mtamolinga tathaneda ka mabebere rsamia ico.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

dru: komédra ikmani kɨkɨ thamdalɨngenga makasi mabeberekoa patarpɨngɨ kɨkɨ kné makela.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.
