Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

dru: otilanma mama iki dane cvalri ka maboroto.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

dru: aki kokola mini cɨvarli ka salké cɨvarli iboro ki mama.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

dru: omɨcɨ mama boetɨ ni noengɨ si thvéké boi mama na.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

dru: tesesɨ kname mama iké tisierka modradrɨke madro ko toboboro masiarara ni.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

dru: iko kogia mili nga ka maragre moso nga si lakthabre moso nga mangkoa ki mama.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

dru: margagi ni nga koko so ka moknia dane berlɨlé maknia mama na.
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

dru: iki 2022 cɨvéllé ka okaigi sého poké mingbongsio ni kecarisia ka odroro manmaninga saké aracɨ ta kcarsia.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

dru: kiboroboro kɨkɨ na mémani nibénma sého solte ngicolo aracɨ name kɨcarsia boi nma mia na cɨkɨlɨ thbarɨ ki sɨsɨgɨ thalmaro.
english: I interviewed ubakɨ, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

dru: matatila kɨname nokémakname kné tébarɨbarɨviyanɨ koboboro nia.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

dru: otilangkoa salkaneni aracɨ ni si la prigo koa thkadaneni cɨkɨcɨkɨlɨ ni.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

dru: kiboroboro knia ka lakoso koborthi mianga aracɨso makorathɨ tométa kné thamdalne aracɨ ta.
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

dru: iko obakɨ ka, "asakéta aracɨ ta kɨcarisia soltɨ ka amani matɨkadrengé aracɨta. aracɨli ka pantomé na cɨkɨcɨkɨlɨli, thkadaneli, sakicoli sokéli takola silpe aracɨta mia."
english: ubakɨ said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

dru: angeresɨ kɨkɨ kakorongo na moa tlangalanga omɨcɨ angidroka ni lɨcenge lapétha akanata kcarsia pavelavela ki kakorongo boi papɨréta.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

dru: madelame ico tlanglanga ni kakorongo tɨngavlo si mongo ka madro olngé ico. lakadro ico mokné mélva tékanani.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

dru: tékanani mongo si vitoro ka sakora margi iké asaké tirimo thithi na botolo madro na brabra mokani tlanglanganme idilipi.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

dru: tékane ni kakorongo ka laké kɨkɨ bila kivkivi brabra niknémia lakoko tililania kné lɨcenge ka angékmanianme droko moknia longé laiya kɨ.
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

dru: isipielɨ angcolo kname longlangé tɨlalanganme iki kakorongo ka takdrengé so iké paspara koa layia.
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

dru: takparali nia kné ka madro kiboborali na ita kɨcarsia akangkana si adrodrokata larigo kɨ na tɨlanglanga na abrélé.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

dru: cɨngɨlɨli skadrelameni akangkanata kakorongo ka sakora kɨ mabebere.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
I arrived at school at seven today.

dru: lribolronga mwadanenga ka sinsi amiakay ka pangcange, "acegecega si sokoboa"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

dru: sabolrobolro, ko singsi wabolro nayyane ko sasiasipane ko kacalrilrisyanane.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Rukai language of numbers.

dru: twapapalra nay ki sinsi silrigo, lasenay nay ko sasiasipane ko pacase.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

dru: makalra ko kibolroli ko kacalrilrisyanane ko vaga.
english: I have learned many Rukai languages.

dru: lokakaiya mwagakwako lokakaiya kiabolrwako ko kacalrilrisyanane ko vaga. lri kawrivako pakilalra ki ina
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Rukai language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

dru: yakay ko tangea ko kaka ka sawvalay, sia Kako taramangealenga si vaeva ko caylini.
english: I have a brother, his name is Kaku, he is 11 years old.

dru: ykaynay ki tayngea ki gako bingkingkiw.
english: We study in the same school.

dru: konako si kaka ka sawvalay taramadalame nay senay.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

dru: madalamako lrededepe, lokatatelradhane maredele nay ka wacekecekele lrededepe.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

dru: madalamako silaliali sitalrailragi lrikarededelenay seasenay si lrededepe.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

dru: amaniako si ama ina kaka ka sawvalay si kaka ka ababay yaelrelrenay.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

dru: ko ama maelrenge ko ama kisace.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

dru: ko ina koladhane ko ina tarasolrasolraw.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

dru: loitavanane ko ama wakacalrilrisiane lomakaorivariva naiyane.
english: My father speaks the Rukai language with us at home.
We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.
My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.
I went out with my mother today.

dru: Kayvaiyane masalaame kay belenge kai makecelre kai madralrangedrange kay vai ngangengerece kay saseverane
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

dru: yakaynay ki cakena ki obolo kanekane kay pange, lako vaivainay lakacolo kay kinawmasane mado
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

dru: la kivagako ki ina anika dodoli ka sobelebelenge
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

dru: Ko ina laiyakay, laolri kela ko valrigi.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

dru: kadrwa ko ememe kaymaongo ngiabwale ka tariao.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

dru: sa lri otavananenay ikadalranane lapelaelako ki tariao ko orikayli
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

dru: anatomane la kai kela ko valrigi apiakivavangeana nako.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

dru: yathili ki danenay ko gakoli lokavaivai panwa dadavacako mogako la dadavacako motavanane
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

dru: kai swaadraw ko gakonay kai tapangale ko banodho la mathingathingalenay makanaelre.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

dru: sanaka lavavalake yaielrelre ikay talailailadhane, karededele ngimaimalri, karededele kalaelaelange.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

dru: ko lasingsi si konay lamaelrenay kivavange, maadraw kay tacekecekelanenay ikay gako.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

dru: lokakaiya tara wasoasoapenay makanaelre pakabola ki takibolrobolrwnenay
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

dru: yakay ko dromane ko waselredre ki lribange yakay ko dromane ko waswape.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

dru: sanaka pacingane gako laswapenay, maparaoralobo makanaelre, lokakaiya laka takabolane kay gakonay
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

dru: koiya mwa cekelako lrikape ki omo.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

dru: maoolaynganay kai madredrele, laka barengerenganako iniane.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

dru: sadrele nakwane kwi omo, lapakane nakwane ko sikwa, lapaongolo nakwane ko oaca.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

dru: kay lredreke ki omo kay sikwa, tengatengane ka malimeme
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

dru: lamialri madalamako kwi lredreke ki omo kwi oca, maiyalri kalimeme lo ongolane
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

dru: lomolringedele, konako si kayngo masilangenay aga ko kodrali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

dru: taykalrane ko aga ki kayngo ko kodrali, yakay ko kange yakay ko koka yakay ko golrogolrane laikaiyana ko kalralringidri.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

dru: samaka tokodralinganay la mwanay lalacengane kilacenge
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

dru: wamalra ngokalra ko kayngo ko orasi tai kocai bai nakwane iloka potavanane laiya nakoane
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

dru: lakiposavako liniane, si iyakay lrikelanako pela drele nomyane.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

dru: kaykameane wailoko nayyane ko sinsi mwa taodrodripane, lasiogonay ilraolraodro si langay ko kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

dru: sa odanenay taodriodripane, ko sinsi la iyakay, "tadhadhamane kwi cocobongota tasolravane kwi lrilrikodro tangisasiavava makanaelre."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

dru: makiocako ki solraw, anikamani kainako wadredrele ki lasolraw.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

dru: wadrelako ko makalra ko adhadhame, yakay belenge ki angato ngipapapalay, ladrelako ki kwici wapece ikay ki adringi ki barongolo ki angato.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

dru: taodriodripane yakay ko zo rigi si lrikolaw, konadroma kainako wadreleana kikay lawaodriodripi, kay tadrelaneli kaykameane kiaragadhako
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

dru: taykalrane ko sasingili, wasasingako lapadrelako ki ama si ina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

dru: lopela lri topalrako ki ama si ina kela
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

dru: kay tatelratelradhane kwako si kaka ka ababay moa Taitong nay lrikape ki agi ki ama ka saovalay.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.
We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

dru: sa daroronay Taitong ko agi ki am ka saovalay la kidresenge nayyane motisaba
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

dru: Kai ngoako thainoane ko tadailane ki dane ki agi ki ama lo hongtingane kai tarathaino ladaroro mado
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

dru: Kwi taykaykayyane ki agi ki ama adethe ki swa adraw ki tapagwagwagwane, lakaredelenay ngolrilrikili mwa ki tapagwagwgwane.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

dru: ikay ki tapagwagwagwane ko agi ki ama la iloko nayyane pakane ki kio si rigi.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

dru: saka maongo lailoko nayyane mo maci kane ko aga.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

dru: Lakakalra ko didiosa maci, lakamani ko ngotobainay mwa kwini.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

dru: sa lri kidailinganay alaka kia kopa ko otobai lakatoasenganay ngobelenge ngokay ki base
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

dru: ladaroronganay Taihoko lakainay thingale loka kiadringainga ko otobay ki agi ki ama.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

dru: saka lavavalakenay yaVedai ko danenay saogakonga latalela mo Pingtong lacekecekelenay ikay dratane.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Vedai. After I started school, we moved to Pingtung and have been living in the city ever since.

dru: samwangako ki daygake laki bolrwako ko patharwakay ki kaodhane ki kacalrisyane, ala thingalako makaelaeela ko ngiradekane ko kakodhane.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

dru: Lakamani, kayasane kay tatelratrlradhane ki kaladralrangedrangane, kwako si kaka lamobalrionay kivavaga ki tarodrawdrange apia thingalenay ki bengkata.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

dru: taramavalrolonga ko tarodrwdrang, ai lodrelane miakaw yaengecengeana.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

dru: lakivagako iniane taypyane ko thingaleso ko vaga, ngodradreadrekadhane macalrosi lokawriva, lamialri thingale ko swa Tayrezokoane, Kecyaneo, si matatobalre ki Dripong.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Rukai, as well as Atayal, Hakka and Japanese.

dru: sakivaganganako alaka singkalavavalake kibolro Dridripongane ko vaga, ko taelrelreini swa Tayrezoko, ikay ki takaoaonganeini lathingale ki swa Kecya, lakamani ko kalrigilini ko taykalrane ko vaga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Atayal, and he knows many Hakkas at work, so he can speak so many languages.

dru: sama kivavaganay, tarodraodrang, lamatikay ki talwalopane ki sidroadromane.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

dru: ono, kainay lrimaka ngolre thingale, ai arasocinay sassing ala lrikilalranay podridringai.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

dru: saka lavavalakako kainako wathingale pangokay ki kakwakodhane ki kacalrisiane, kay takakacalrisyaneli yakay ko takalromalaneli.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

dru: saka kalranga ko thingaleli la arodradraranako taka Ngodradrekadhaneli ko taokalrivilane.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Rukai is unique and something to be proud of.

dru: kaykameane loka miwaobo lriotavanane kwi agili ka sawvalay.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

dru: konako si kayngo, wamwanay talacengane ki siwbai langai ko koka padolro agane ko kwaobo si pakane ki agili ka sawvalay.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

dru: ngoakakaynay talacengane ki siwbai. kwi siwbai ki talacengane lakataykalrane ko taokamanimani ko lacenge.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

dru: lalangainay ko kongsingccay, toba, si dodoli ka daykongo.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

dru: kodra yathili siwbai ki madro ki angato kodra lawpang laiyajkay, "kay pangodraleli si momo sangalwalo langadha ngobebekele."
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

dru: ngoakakayinay siwbai ki botolo lawpang laiyakay, "lrilangaiso ko manemane? kaykameane maricoro kay koka si lakadraw, ko vaeva tolro ka idai."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

dru: kwi kayngo makocingalrenga laiya, lakivaga ki lawpang todwadwadha.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

dru: ai kwi laopange amiyakay syamadwainga kai lrimakakivalanga ko nidang.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

dru: pasiagisi ka lawpange laiyakay, bwala langadha kay kangeli, kay kangeli madwai laka tadradraw.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

dru: sakabilrilanenga lalangainay ko koka si kange, laotavanane todamai tangea ki cokoi.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

dru: pangoadingiva ko agili ka sawvalay iyakay kay takwapingane kiarimo kai patelrai, lobalrithinga ki niciwbi lriwbalrivako.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

dru: kayngo amyakay, makalra kay agali, dawla latakane makanaelre!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

dru: wadaolonay ki retesanenay lakarededelenay kisopilri kay kwabo.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

dru: yakay ko papalrali ki bolro sya Lioco, laka takarimirimorane ko lamanemaneini
english: I have a classmate named Liucu, he often forgets to bring things.

dru: lokibolrobolro, lakisalro ki papalraini ko sapacapacasane, sasakisakidrane ka gomo si coming.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

dru: sangovale sangoposale sangotolrolo, la pakisalro iniane ko lamanemane makanaelre.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

dru: ai yakay ko malisi ko kakodhaneini, kiasalro lakai saolriolri.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.
In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.
One day, we all went on an outing together.

dru: ikay kadadalranane la apimolricongo, ai lakarimoro ko sasakisakidrane ko senate.
english: On the way, Liucu wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

dru: lakisalro ki papalraini ki bolro ko sasakisakidrane ko senate., ai makitoamiakay tobalre makanaelre, kainako wailoko.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

dru: lagelrethe kwi Lioco, lakalisi iyakay, anokai pakisalro nakwane makanaelre ko sasakisakidrane ko senate!
english: Liucu burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

dru: latobalre ko papalraini ki bolro, iyakay anikamani yai kaiso ngiailoko si lopakisalrwane moswane ko lamanemane lakaiso saolriolri!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

dru: sakakaiyane samogako langolalakese mogako kwi Lioco, ko kisalroini ki papalraini ki bolro lasaolri liniane patolre ko lamanemane.
english: The next day at school, Liucu arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

dru: lakaiseasene ki papalraini ki bolro kwi Lioco, si iyakay lringiailokonganako ko lamanemaneli, ko syaswalane taobangalranenomi pakisalro nakawane maelanenga.
english: Liucu apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

dru: taroaloalopo ikay ki cekelenay ko ama.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

dru: saka lavavalakeana ko ama si agini lokamaongo moalatadre, lailoko ko bakale si kwange.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

dru: loka liarenga lailoko ko panalini ko waodriodripi.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

dru: yakay loka baboi yakay loka boboto avavale ikay ko padavathane.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

dru: Lapavavalanenga ikay ki sangangodane ki cekele, pakisopilri ki cekele.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

dru: laka tamakavaladhaneli ki ama ko atopalrane alopo.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

dru: ko ama laiyakay lokadraongaso, nawilokonga moswane alopo.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

dru: kay yacekele kay lamalala arakay ko kateme ki waodriodripi, lakalrigili aratokolro si lrenege drepete ki kateme.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

dru: ko ama malrigili darepe ko satokolrane kateme, ko ama laiyakay, kikay sarakayyane saramete ki padavathane, lripodriadringayta drele ko tangokakaiyane ki waodriodripi kay kateme la sarare ko kateme pikay ki tangokakaiyane ki waodriodripi ko kadalranane dadavace.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

dru: pakay ko asara topapalrane ki tarodraodrange alopo, lokakaiya lakicakwanako dringi kay dringaili, ikasolivate pwalra ki waodriodripi.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

dru: sadrele ko ama laiyakay nakwane, lokabibilrili lritara kamaniako kodra magagarangenga ka taralopo.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

dru: Kayasasane maadraonganako watokodra ko boo si lraili, topalra ki ama karedele alopo.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

dru: loobalrio, lalri pakisopilri ki sakacekele ko nipanane ko waodriodripi.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

dru: Ko ama laiyakay lrikiaseaseneta ki aidridringane tapataromarane lakakalra kay panata kay waodriodripi.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.
I was late for school this morning.
When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

dru: sakibolrobolronay mwaridrosako ki, papalrali drele ki hongo.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

dru: sasikisikinginay pakyasalro, ko sapacapacasane si sasopisopilrane ko papalrali.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

dru: ko talragili sya Retage, mialri ka lalake ki Ngodradrekay.
english: My good friend's name is Ratage, and he is also an Rukai child.
We study together in the Vedai tribe.

dru: Tataelreanenay kilalalra loabolro ko marodrawdrangenay, malrigilinay Ngodradreadrekadhane.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Rukai proficiently.

dru: Maelrengako si kabitolro, ka Ratage koladhane si edrekane.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Ratage is short and thin.

dru: Mapabibitiki kay Retage lakadalameta ki laso.
english: Ratage is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

dru: Ngodokay ki swagako kaykameane taykalrane ko tapakalrwalromalane.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

dru: yakay ko mabibibili, watetere ki malri walailailay si wadralray.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.
When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

dru: ai acegecegako si pacongolo papococobongo lrabwale.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.
Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

dru: kainako wamalra ko icibange, ai kyaragadhako, asiloiyane patwalrepengako kikalromale.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

dru: Koiya taroadrosanay ki ama lrikape ki agi ki ama ka saovalay.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

dru: madola ko drapale ki agi ki ama ka sawvalay.
Ka laso amiyakaynayyane mabolroto ka talrogolrogane ki daane.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

dru: Ka laso sapodriadriadringai ki talrogolrogane. twalay ki talrogolrogane toverevere molebe.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

dru: Ko ama wailoko ko beate ki lwange si sabiki bai ki agiini ka sawvalay.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

dru: Sakalaelaelaengenay ki agi ki ama idane. pakyasopilri ko taykalrane ko abolro.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

dru: Salrikatwasengako ko agi ki ama, ladrengedrengere nakwane madraongaso si aokathriringaso.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

dru: Laiyako kayki agi ki ama. longodringainga kwi drapaleso. kelanga nayyanane kivavange.
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

dru: Saka2022kacayli, kay siho pakaygi ko kacalrilrisyanan ki nibongosiw ko nagane.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

dru: Maolainga kivavaga ki siho ko akasivavalane nagane kacalrilrisyane ki nibongosiw acengecenge ki cekele Kolele Gadho.
english: I interviewed Kulele Gadhu, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

dru: Mapapelaelanganay ki laso ko alrikapane kayki taelratelradhane mwaki dane lini.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

dru: Ikayki takivavaganeli ko tatwaladhane ki naganeini lasiwkaynga nakwane ki wacekecekeleini si cekeleini.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

dru: Lakivagako inyane asokakecenge pabalrithi kay nagane malisi ko natapangimiamyame?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

dru: Laiyakay tobalre nakwane, asiloiyane kay pacase ki ciokoko kailrimaka pacengecenge pelaela ko naganeini, kaydroma laikay lo daolo "kosinsi" kavay ki laso, lamatilrolropi.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Ku Xian Sheng

dru: Kolele Gadho kay kacalrilrisyanane pacase ko nagane patengatengane ka naganeta. kay naganali atalingikayyane ki zokonay retetesanenay takawmaomasanenay, anatomane laarotapangale ko kacalrisyane pasyaolrolri ko naganeini."
english: Gadhu said, "The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group, our family, our identity. I hope more fellow tribespeople can reclaim their own names."

dru: Koiya twapalrako ki kayngo momacisiobay, lailoko ko ngilralredrekeini ko lacenge, ko kacalrilrisyanane si bai nayyane.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

dru: Madalame kay mapapangale kay siobay ki kayngo, tapangale ko walangay kay kamangolo ngipalrilriding Ka nasobi lapalalava kane ko todamay ki kayngo.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

dru: ko todamaini ko maongo si doray ka pagay malimeme toramoro kiamorikay ki badhabadha, lakela makanaelre ki siobaynay siogo.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

dru: Laagaga kay kayngo ladawdaolako ki badhabadha. yathilako karalealeale, "ngilralredrekenay kaylacenge, kaikanipokeselyrane, bwala kirimwa langay."
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

dru: Lapadalro kingolre kay siobaynay laiyajay kay kayngo, "amani saparaloboso."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

dru: kayaongane kyabolrwako patharokkay ki sopongo si akaneane kacalrisyane ki lrigilane. kilringaw ko sakwalrialri mado siwbay.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

dru: sadrelako ki kayngo marabere pakay kiakaneane ki sidroadromane arodradraranako toramoro si sasipyane.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

dru: kaiasaa mwagakoa ko ki pito ki toki ki myalrealre.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

dru: aikibolronga nai, samodane ki takibolrobolrowa ko singsi, ko pangcang amiya ikai:" idiya! sokoba!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

dru: la akwadrao nai singsi. sabao miya.
sa kibolro nai, ko singsi wabolro naiya ahakai ko kacalrilrisiyana wasipi.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Rukai language of numbers.

dru: twapapalra nai silrigo, la bolro naiya ahasenai wasipi.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

dru: makalra ko kibolro li si thingale ko kacalrilrisiyana.
english: I have learned many Rukai languages.

dru: mwagakoa ko loadhane, kyabolrowa ko ko kacalrilrisiyana loadhane, aipakilalra ko ki ina.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Rukai language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

dru: ko nagane li ki sya Moakai.
ko nagane ki ama sya Legeai.
ko nagane ki ina sya Alaelrepe.
tangea ko kake ka saowalai, sya Sakino. tahamangealanga si ea ko caili ini.
english: I have a brother, his name is Sakinu, he is 11 years old.
We study in the same school.

dru: konako si kake tahamadalame nai senai.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

dru: madalama ko lwangoi, lo taibalribalriva, mahedele nai ka wacekecekele lwangoi.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

dru: madalama ko kisodalro ko baowa ka talrailragi, wadolro mado taelre senai si langoi.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.

dru: taelrea ko ki ama, ina, kake ka saowalai si kake ka ababai.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

dru: ko ama maelrenge, ko ama kisace.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

dru: ko ina koladha, ko ina kwisang.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

dru: lo ikai taowana ko ama ahakai ko kacalrilrisiyana kaohiva naiya.
english: My father speaks the Rukai language with us at home.

dru: lo taibalribalriva ki kaladrangedranga mwabalriyo nai.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

dru: konako si lakake mahedele nai malra ko takohaoho.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.

dru: kaiasaa mahedela ko ki ina avaevaehe.
english: I went out with my mother today.

dru: sa avaiya waledra sobelebelenge, kadrowa ka makecelre kadrowa ka wadrangedrange, mangangehece ko saseveha.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

dru: yakai nai ki obobola kwanekane ko mingpao, ko vai pasaelre ki kinaomasane nai pakacolo.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

dru: la kitobolrowa ko ki ina, ani kadiheele sobelebelenge?
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

dru: laiya ikai ko ina, tali aikela ko sedreke.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

dru: sa amaongo kadrowa ko emeeme sobelebelenge, ngyaboale ko tahiyao.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

dru: ikai kaelrelrea, la kitobiya ko ki tahiyao.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

dru: anatoma lakai kela ko sedreke, apya kivaevangeanana ko.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

dru: ko gako li yathili ki dane nai, loadhana wadadavaca ko mogako, la dadavace motaowana.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

dru: mwatiki ko gako nai, tabekele ko sito, konai mathingathingale nai makanaelre.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

dru: sana alavavalake yahobo ikai talrabwabwala, taelre ngimalri, taelre kalaelange.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

dru: ko singsi nai taelre naiya kivaevange, myaki nai wacekecekele.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

dru: loadhana waswape nai, aipakabola nai soape ki takibolrobolrowane nai.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

dru: yakai ko waselredre ki lribange, yakai ko waswape.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

dru: waswape nai sana akalyopa, mapalribilribolo nai, ko gako nai mabola loadhana.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

dru: kodhaa, mwa cekela ko lrikape ki omo.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

dru: maolainga nai kai macaceele, mabahengehengana ko iniya.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

dru: sa ceele nakowa ko omo, wapakane nakowa ko swika, paongolo nakowa ko ociya.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

dru: malimeme ko lredreke ki omo ko swika, patengatenga ka malimeme.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

dru: miyalri madalama ko ko ociya ki omo, miyalri kalimeme.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

dru: sa molringedele, taelrea ko ki kaingo waaga ko kodrali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

dru: makalra ko aga ki kaingo, yakai ko kaange, tahokoko, tahamonage, laikai ko dingidingi.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

dru: sa makakane nai, la owa nai lalacenga kilacenge.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

dru: ko kaingo amalra ko makalra ko tai si kocai bwaai pailoko nakowa.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

dru: kyaposaowa ko liniya, si nao kelanga lobibilrili mya liniya.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

dru: kaiasaa, ko singsi aiiloko naiya mwaki tasyavavavaa ki odryodripi, yahobo nai ikai saolatadra lwangai ko kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

dru: sa modaanenga nai, ko singsi amiyaikai, kwani cocobongo ladhadhame, talilrilrikodro lalawlai, ngikakamaniya syavava.
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

dru: mwakolodra ko ki alawlai, lakoni ko kalrase li mwa ceele.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

dru: wacela ko ko makalra ko adhadhame, yabelenge ki angato ngipapapalai, la ceela ko ko loo ko waapece ibahongolo ki angato.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

dru: ikai ki tasyavavavaa ki odryodripi, yakai ko zoo, higi, si lrikolao, kadrowana ka waceele ikai laodryodripi kai, kyahagadha ko sa ceela ko kaiasaa.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

dru: makalra ko sasingi li, aipacela ko ki ama si ina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

dru: lobibilrili aikahedela ko ki ama si ina kela.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

dru: kai taibalribalriva kai, konako si kake amwa nai Taito lrikape ki agi ki ama.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

dru: twalai nai Taihoko ngokai ki kisa moTaito.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

dru: sa kela nai Taito, ko agi ki ama waongting ki didyosa kidresenge naiya.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

dru: adethe tisaba ko daane ki agi ki ama, padalro nai sikela.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

dru: adethe ki agi ki ama ko mwaadrao ka tapagwagwagowa, mahedele nai ngotokotoko mwa.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

dru: ikai tapagwagwagowa, ko agi ki ama wailoko naiya pwakane ki kiyo si higi.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

dru: sa amaongo, mahedele nai momaci kwane ko aga.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

dru: makalra ko didyosa maci, lakoni ko ngokai nai ki otobai.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

dru: sa aidavacenga nai, sika kyakopa ko otobai, langokainga nai ki base dwavace.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

dru: syaolringa nai moTaihoko, kyadringadhangaini ko agi ki ama ko otobai ini.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

dru: saalavavala ko, ko daane nai yakai Labowa, sa mogakongana ko, la talela nai papiya Akao, ikai paihange cekecekecekele.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Labuwa. After I started school, we moved to Pingtung and have been living in the city ever since.

dru: sa kadrawngana ko, lai kibolrowa ko ko pathahokai ki kakoakodha ki kacalrisiya, thingalenga ko taikalra makaelaela ko kakoakodha ikaikai Taiwang.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

dru: lakoni, ikai taibalribalriva ki kaladrangedranga, konako si kake la mocekele nai kitobobolro ki tahodrawdrange, api thingale ko kakoakodhane nai ka Ngodradrekai.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

dru: kaivai tahodrawdrange tahamavalrolonga ko caili ini, ai loceela myaki yacengecenge.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

dru: kyatobolrowa ko iniya ko thingale ini ko vaga, lo ngodradreadrekadha macalrosi, miyalri thingale ko Dridripongana, paihaihangana si amilryalrikana.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Rukai, as well as Japanese, Hokkien and English.

dru: sa kitobolrongana ko iniya wathingala ko, sika kyabolro saalavavalake ko Dridripongana, ko taowane ini Amilrika, laikai ki tatwatwatomanane ini kisodalro ko takalra ko paihange, lakoni thingale ko taikalra ka vaga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an American, and he knows many Chinese at work, so he can speak so many languages.

dru: sa kitobobolro nai iniya, matikai ko taikalra ko lrigila lo alopo koigayga.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

dru: eene kadrowaka makathingale demedeme, ai ahakai nai ko soci tokacodo, lai makadolronga nai kilalra topodriyadringai.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

dru: saalavavalaka ko kadrowa ka wathingale ikai kakoakodhane nai, matinino ko takakacalrisiyanane li.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

dru: sa haokakalra ko thingale li, haongyathathingala ko lo amani mado ko Ngodradrekai, amani ko mwakalrivili, amani ko adolrowane mado ngidradraha.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Rukai is unique and something to be proud of.
My younger brother is going home this evening.

dru: konako si kaingo amwa nai maci lwangai ko tahokoko, padolro ko malimeme ka kwaobo pwakane ki agili.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

dru: sa lribate nai ki talacenga, makalra ko tawnyalralra ka lacenge.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

dru: walangai nai ko kongsingcai, toba si daikongo.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

dru: ko yathili ki syobai ki madro ka taoki laiyaikai, malimeme kaivai pangodrale li si momo, lwangadha ngobekele.
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

dru: la langai nai ko pangodrale si momo.
sa lribate nai ki tabotola, kodra taoki laiyaikai ailangai so ko manema? kaivai tahokoko kaiasaa maadrao si kahicoho tolro ka idai ko ea.
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

dru: kao kaingo makocingalre laiya, la kitobolro ki taoki loaimaka topadolro ko bekela.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

dru: kwani taoki latobalre mapadolronga, kadrowaka aimaka kivalanga.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

dru: kodra yathili ka taoki laiyaikai nyama lwangadha ikai kaange li, madrao si lakapadolro.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

dru: sabilrila walangai nai ko tahokoko si kaange motaowana waga pasiete ki cokoi.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

dru: ko agili la pangodingva myaikai twahanao patoicilri paibalriyo naiya, lo adrihainga ki bibilrili aimaka mobalriva ko.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

dru: kao kaingo amiyaikai kaiwaagangana ko tothathathaa, dwaola nikela makanaelre kwane!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

dru: ladawdaolo nai ki lahetesa talrailragi, ko wakela kalringolo kisopilri ikaivai makaelaelaela ka kwaobo.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

dru: yakai ko sapasyasilange li ko sya Usao, wasavidhi kahimoho iloko ko lamanemane ini.
english: I have a classmate named Usau, he often forgets to bring things.

dru: lo kibolrobolro, kyasalro ki sapasyasilange ini ko cingpi, sasopisopilra si cyomingi.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

dru: ngivale, ngiposale, ngitolrolo, pakyasalroana iniya makanaelre.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

dru: ai, yakai ko ngyalisiya ko kakodhane ini, wasavidhi kisalro sikai saolryolri.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

dru: sabilrilanenga kadrowa ka apya pakisalro iniya makanaelre.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

dru: yakai saavaivai, konai makanaelre mahedela nai kivaevange.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

dru: ikai kaelrelrea, kao Usao apya mobingziyonga, ai, mahimoho iloko ko wisengce.
english: On the way, Kacaw wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

dru: la kisalro ki sapasyasilange ini, ai amiya ikai tobalre iniya, makanaelre miyalriya ko kadrowa ka wailoko.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

dru: kao Usao la tobi ki samama. la kalisi myaikai, asi ani kai pakisalro nakowa makanaelre!
english: Usau burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

dru: ko sapasyasilange lapelaela iniya, amanisa kaiso ngiyaililoko, lo pakisalro mosowa ko lamanema, lakai so saolryolri!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

dru: sa mogako laadhana, ngwalalakese mogako kao Usao, la saolri demedeme idra kisalro ini ki sapasyasilange ini.
english: The next day at school, Usau arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

dru: sabao laiya kao Usao ki sapasyasilange ini, laiya ikai lo bibilrili aingiyailokongana ko, la kyaseasene ki sapasyasilange ko tapakisalrowa iniya ko lamanema.
english: Usau apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

dru: ko ama taha alwalopo ikai ki cekele nai.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

dru: sa alroladha ko, ko ama si agiini wadavace lo amaongo, iloko ko lrabo si kwange.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

dru: lo kaledra, la kainganai iloko ko pana lini.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

dru: yakailo ababoi, yakailo alrava, yakailo apadamatha.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

dru: yakai sakakela ki cekele pavalavala ko pana, pakisopilri ki kinaowacekela.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

dru: loiya makavaladha ko ki ama, api topalra walopo.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

dru: ko ama laiya ikai, lo kadraonga so nao iloko mosowa.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

dru: ko saowalai ki cekele yakailo ahakai ko kateme pwana, wadahepe ko nipalreea si taenge tokolro.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

dru: ko ama malrigili ahakai ko tokolro, amiyaikai sahakaiya pwalra ki padamatha, waceele mado ko dalrane ki odryodripi, pyakai mado ki tangokakaiyane lini potokolro.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

dru: ngwalai ko asaha topalra ki tahodrawdrange walopo, kyacakowana ko loadhane dwahepe ko tokolro, aipadalronga laipana kai tokolro li.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

dru: sa ceele ko ama amiyaikai nakowa lobibilrili aitaha amani so ko mahakace ka tahaalopo.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

dru: kaiasaa madrawngana ko, waangeala ko ki boo si lraili li, topalra ki ama walopo.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

dru: la pakisopilri ki kinaowacekela ko pana li.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

dru: ko ama amiyaikai, aikiyaseasene ta ki lacocongolane ta ko sasobolrobolrowa mitaa, la patahomaha ko makalra ko pana.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.
I was late for school this morning.

dru: samogakowako, mahimohako kai iloko ko kabange.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

dru: sakibolrobolronai, taelreako ki hedelaneli ceele ko hongo.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

dru: sasikinginai, ko hedelaneli pakisalro nakowa ko cingpi si sasopisopilra.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

dru: ko singsi amiyaikai nakowa, lobibilrili sahangidrakaala
ko talragili sya Sola, miyalri ka lalake ki Ngodradrekai.
english: My good friend's name is Sula, and he is also an Rukai child.

dru: taelrenai ikai ki cekelenai Labowa kibolrobolro.
english: We study together in the Labuwa tribe.

dru: tataelreanenai kilalalra ki mahodrange lo tomaolai, taha malrigilinai Ngodradreadrekadha.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Rukai proficiently.

dru: maelrengako si kabitolro, kao Sola edreka si kahilai.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Sula is short and thin.

dru: kao Sola pahahakaca, madalame makanaelre iniya.
english: Sula is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

dru: kayasaa ongdokai ki swa gako, kay swa gako pyaiya ko taikalra ko amakalrwalromala.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

dru: yakai ko mabilibilibili, watetehe ko malri, lrabowale, odolri si walraili.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.
When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.
But I stood up and continued running forward.

dru: sakelako ki sakaamodo kodra laomase kyahahagai makanaelre.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

dru: eene kadrowa ka amalra ko icibange, ai kyahahagadhako, asiloiyaa twalrepengako ikay kikalromaleli.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

dru: kodhaa konako si ama walrikapenai ki agiini.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

dru: ko agi ki ama madola ko drapaleini.
peaelaela naiya, ko cavalriya ki daane mabolroto.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

dru: sa topodringadringai ki cavalriya, twalai cavalriya mocilri.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

dru: ko ama wailoko ko beate ki lwange si sabiki bwai ki agiini.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

dru: konako si agi ki ama yakainai daane kalaelaelange, peaelaela nakowa ko makalra ko maolai.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

dru: sa aidavacenai, ko agi ki ama waseba nakowa madraongaso miya, lahao kathahihi ngisaowalai.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

dru: amiyako ikai, lo modringainga ko drapaleini, aikelananako liniyana kivaevange.
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

dru: ikay ki 2022 ka caili, kay swasiho yahobo mapelaela pathahokai ikay nibongsiyo ki kacalrisiya ko adolrowa drepele ahakai ko kacalrilrisiyana pwacase ko nagane.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

dru: kiatobolrowako ko maolainga papiya ki siho kihahibici ko akipalrainga drepele ahakai ko kacalrilrisiyana pwacase pikai ki nibongsiyo ka yacengecenge ka sya Cemelresai.
english: I interviewed Cemelresai, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

dru: mapapalrainginai lo ataibalriva aiowako liniyana kitobobolro iniya.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

dru: ikay ki takitobobolrowaneli, papiya nakowa ngipapelaela ko tatoaladha ko naganeini, la iloko nakowa pathingale ki wacekecekeleini, si cekeleini.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

dru: kyatobolrowako iniya aso kakeecengenga naobalrithilringa ki nagane miya, kay sakokakodhaa pwacase ki nagane malisi?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

dru: kao Cemelresai amiyaikai, ko nyahakaiya ko kacalrilrisiyana pwacase ka nagane amani ko patengatenga ka naganenai. kay naganeli sapatothingala ko takasomanemananenai, cocongolanenai, takaomawmasanenai, anatoma lahao takalra ko myanakowa ka kacalrisiya la palraingi kyomao pasiyolri ko lanaganelini.
english: Cemelresai said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

dru: kodhaa twapalrako ki kaingo momaci tosyobai, ko kaingo wailoko ko makalra ko ngilralredrekeini ka lacenge, lapiya twakanea ko kacalrilrisiyana ka lakanea bwai ki omase.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

dru: madalame makanaelre ikay syobai ki kaingo, ko tavangolo si cemeameha takalra ko walangai, takalra ko omase ko wakela palalava ko todamaiini.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and Chinese Angelica, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

dru: ko againi ko mawngo si dohai malimeme tohamoho, laahakai ko bolabolai si makao cehebe ko beate, ko tasangosadha wathehepe pakainganai ko takalra ko badhabadha, wakela ikay syobainai siyogo makanaelre.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

dru: lo agaga kao kaingo, yathilako dwaodaolo ko badhabadha, yathilako walealeale, kay lalacenge ngilralredrekenai, kadrowa ko sababoo, nyama lrwabwala lwangai.
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, "The vegetables are self-grown, all-natural and organic! Come and buy now!"

dru: ko kilangainai ko lamanema padalro si kalrepenge, kao kaingo amiyaikai, amanisa ikaiso palribolo lakoni.
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, "It's all thanks to your help."

dru: kay takakadra kay, makalra ko kibolroli pathahokai ikay kacalrilrisiyana ka lawacebecebe si lakanea ka thingala, la kipabalra ko sakwalriyalri lo tosyobadha.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

dru: loceelako ki kaingo ko hangehanganeini kay pathahwakai ki taleke ki kacalrisiya, ngyadradrahanako si ikai ko lrigo.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

dru: sesane ka pito na koli'i ko mowali gako.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

dru: amwanga na zikang, singsi ka la oda'ane mwa tasolasolatane, pang-cange la 'apobaka, "'id'iya! sokoba!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

dru: kosolatiname ka paigo'o namiya kisingisina sasysipi na wakacaisisiyne.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Rukai language of numbers.

dru: 'angopapa kiname singsiane wasyasipi, wathenay kiname na wasyasipi na thenay.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.
I have learned many Rukai languages.

dru: pava'iyane kakemwagako pava'iyane kake kicawane kwacaisisiyane. 'apobaka mekake pabiciingi titinane.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Rukai language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

dru: na kay cicavilika wata ma ngesale ngana civilili.
'iyakay nakowa 'asaseane na sawalay na kaka acinika gilagilaw.
english: I have a brother, his name is gilagilaw, he is 11 years old.

dru: ta'aese kiname 'ikay na gako sola solate.
english: We study in the same school.

dru: kaka si kake ka madalame kiname the nay.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

dru: madalame kake lwangolwan. ta'isasadrane ka 'angese kiname ka thakada'ane mwa lwangolangoy.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

dru: madalame kake na ba'owane na la'osay angese kiname thenay lwangolangoy.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.

dru: da'aniname ka iyakay 'a too na lamengame.
english: There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

dru: kake si tatava, titina, kaka sawalay. si kaka 'abayane.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

dru: tatavinakowaka ma'aagae. tatavi nakoa ka kisace.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

dru: titina kowa ka mailay titinakowa ka kwisange.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.
My father speaks the Rukai language with us at home.
We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

dru: kake si kaka 'angese kiname mwa bwadra na takoapange.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.
I went out with my mother today.

dru: viviva'ane tabelengane ka mathao, va'iyane ka ikakece si ikaapa'a, besebese ka mabalesebese.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

dru: 'iyakay kiname dida'ane taswaoswaovane kwane na ming-pao, kokoli'i ka wapava'i bwatiname, sawkoa malabeabee.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.

dru: viva'anenga ka tahelengane ka wabaythi matileange.
english: In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

dru: kyaboboo kake titinane, akwani tabelengane patasini ka 'atadileleangini?
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

dru: titina ka 'apobaka, kadromane ka no sebee ami.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

dru: ma'awbo tabelengane ka kadroa na koongo, 'abwale na taiyaw.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.
On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

dru: saamanga si i'awkay na sesbee, 'api 'abebebee la kake.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

dru: gakoili ka 'iyakay da'aniname cigi'ane, pava'iyane kake dwavadavace mwa gako, si dwavadavace sivii.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

dru: isakwadraw gakoname, ikadraw na sito, maygoigo'ane maesale.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

dru: sana 'avalavalake ka 'iyaobo 'ikay 'ongdozio, ta'aese 'angi na malri, ta'aese 'avavane.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

dru: ki singsi ka ta'aese namiya 'angi, gako ka amiya na tawmomo na thakada'ane.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

dru: pava'iyane kiname sozi, pabola'a nakay tasolasolatane.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

dru: 'iyakay na coaw wadrisidrisi na ta'avangane, 'iyakay na coaw waswape.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

dru: waswape kiname gako ma'akaynoinonga, matibocobocongo kiname, gako ka pava'iyane mabola'a.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

dru: kosi'a ka, amwa kake tecekecekelane swapepeale twamane.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.
We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

dru: tawmo ko cengelini koa ka pakane nakoa na si-kwa, la pa'ongolo nakoa na 'ocya.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

dru: doko'ini ki tawmo ko si-kwa ka malimeme sawkoa, maagi'i ko kwanimade.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

dru: madalame kake 'ocyaini ki tawmo, maagi'i ko 'ongolimade.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

dru: viva'ane ka takadrosa kiname ki takawngo do'o na kidrali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

dru: takawngo ka tyakanekane maagi'i na kidrali, 'iyakay na ka'ange 'iyakay na tawkoko 'iyakay na tangetange, la 'iyakay laana tawlolo.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.
After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

dru: takawngo ka amalra 'angiyadraw na bwathi, tay si tangavane bwa'ay koa, wameca 'abee mya.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

dru: amwa kake nyane posao, 'awkay lami kake cengele mwane.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

dru: sesane ka wameamece namiya ki singsi mwa tong-'o-ying, la 'ikay kiname balingtavane matilibi lwangay na kipe.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

dru: moda'aniname tong-'o-ying ka, la 'apobaka ki singsi, "talocobongane ka alralrame, ikodrangane ka swa'a, mo'angekidredrema komo mwa cengecengele."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

dru: 'akolodro kake na swa'a, nikwadra icengele kake na swa'a.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

dru: wacengele kake 'angiyadraw na alralrame, 'iyakay 'angato agae 'angopalapalay, la cengele laa kokongo 'ikay ta'angatongatoane na mawbong 'adringi syaeke.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

dru: tong-'o-ying 'adringi ka 'iyakay na zo, 'ema si ikolaw, icengelela kake ami nakay na golagolay, sesane ka mabeabee kake nakay tacengelanili.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

dru: madraw ko pakisyasingili, pacengele tatava si titina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

dru: bilanenga ka no 'angese mikiname tatava si titina 'awkay.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

dru: kikay ta'isasadrane va'iyane ka, kake si kaka 'abayane ka amwa Taito swapepeale tatavane.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.
We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

dru: mwaninga Taito, 'angosengepae 'awkay tisyaba dresenge namiya ki tatava.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

dru: tisyaba ka ika'adavili da'anini ki tatava ki 'Ase, 'angesangepaemade ka wadodao'o kimade mwa.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

dru: tatava 'Ase da'anini ka wadali tathadethade'ane, 'angeese kiname 'angotawngatingi mwa tathadethade'ane.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

dru: 'ikay tathadethade'ane, tatava 'Ase wameamece namiya pakane na saw'iyo si 'ango'ema.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

dru: ma'awbonga ka, la 'angese kiname mwa tokosi kwane na do'o.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

dru: tokosi ka madraw na sangepae, nikwaname i'ango'otobay mwa drayne.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

dru: ta'avagay myaname ka, laso igo'o kiname kya'opa na coaw 'otobay swaongaynga kiname 'angobase 'avagay.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

dru: nakay ka 'abeenga kiname mwa Taihoko, amiyani ko 'otobayni ki tatava 'Ase ka mwakononga nyani.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

dru: ko 'avalavalakili ka 'iyakay kiname Kongadavane, ko patekedriname ka la 'aela kiname mwa Takaw sikace.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Kongadavane. After I started school, we moved to Kaohsiung and have been living in the city ever since.

dru: ko mwalinga daigake ka la kica'oane kake na tolwanini na kacaisyane, lasoigo'o kake Taiwan kacaisyane na ma'ielela na bengka.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

dru: nikwani nakay cicavili hoyasemi kake si kaka la 'abee kiname mwa tacekecekelane kiboboo na maodrange. taigo'o na bengkaname mya.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

dru: maodrange ka watamavaolonga na cavilini, makasi cengelimade ka amiya na 'athabaela.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

dru: la kiboboo kake nyane maniigo'iso na baka mya, maygili 'apobaka na wadrekadrekane, waigo'o na wapakikisane. wakokaomane si wa'amolrilrikane.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Rukai, as well as Hokkien, Japanese and English.

dru: ko boboilinga lasoigo'o kake ko 'avalavalakini ka kyaca'oane na wakokaomane, palangini ka pakisa, si ta'akomolanini ka la paygoigo'ane na taligaykoko, nikwani igo'o 'angiyadraw na ma'akabakanga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Chinese, and he knows many foreign at work, so he can speak so many languages.

dru: ko mabakabakainame ka lapatolotolnga kiname taiyanini na walopo.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

dru: itakaigo'ane kiname bicingi, makasi syakay kiname na so-ci lo-ing, la doo la kiname pa'ingcege biciingi.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

dru: 'avalavalakili ka itakaigo'ane kake na bengka kacaisyane, 'angi ka'ino kake taakacaisyanili.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

dru: madrawininga igo'ili la kabeabeenga kake, 'angipakileve thakongadavane kake mya.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Kongadavane is unique and something to be proud of.

dru: sesane masaemesemini ka 'abee ami kigili mwa da'ane.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

dru: kake si takawngo ka wamikiname talangalangaane lwangay na tawkoko. paagele do'o na ki'awbo pakane giliya.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

dru: waibate kiname talangalangaane na lacenge, madraw na maagi'i na lacenge.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

dru: lalangay kiname na 'ingcay toba'a si ningzingi.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

dru: cigi'ane walangalangay na madro lawpange ka la'apobaka, "pangodralili si somomo ka malimeme. lwangaa 'angititi'ici."
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

dru: walangay kiname na pangodrale si somomo.
laibate kiname talangalangaane na bwate, lawpange la'apobaka, "mani langayaniso? sesane na tawkoko ka tawmomo mamitee, sesesane ka too na idai na payso.
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

dru: takawngo ka makocingay laya, lakiboboo lawpangane. doo myaso tipadodoo 'angititi'ici.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

dru: makasi lawpange ka la'apobaka, "mapadodoonga, dooiyanga oalralra."
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

dru: cigi'ane lawpange la'apobaka, "ngoalra lwangaa ka'angili, ka'angili ka tawmomo si lakapadodoo."
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

dru: biilanenga lalangay kiname na tawkoko si ka'ange, la'abee kiname do'o pasiéte cekei.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

dru: la dingva ki gili pa'abee, betai ka i'isasadra, sakasokobanenga ka doo mikake 'abee mya.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

dru: takawngo ka la'apobaka do'onga 'akathay nakay, kokwava tatakaese kwane.
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!
We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

dru: 'iyakay 'asaseane na soi'anili acini ka 'Aase, 'ataleese maimoo wamece na ma'akoanga.
english: I have a classmate named 'Aase, he often forgets to bring things.

dru: solatiname ka lakisodame soi'aniname na 'ingpice, sadrisidrisi si ciwmingi.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

dru: kovasale, koposale, kotoolo maesale doo pasodamenyane.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

dru: makasi, 'iyakay na makoace ka sakaini 'ataleese kisodame na ma'akakoanga si isavivii.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.
In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.
One day, we all went on an outing together.

dru: ikainame dadaane, 'Aase la'apiyowa bingzyo makasi lakaimoo na wisengce.
english: On the way, 'Aase wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

dru: kosisodame na wisengce laya soi'anini, makasi lakaesele 'akobii, iamece kinamemya.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

dru: 'Aase ka sotobinga, lakagi'imoco, akwamo ka nimipasodame nakoa na wisengce.
english: 'Aase burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

dru: soi'anini ka la 'apobaka nyane, nikwani ka i'angiamece koso, no pasodamimade mosoa na ma'akakwanga koso ka isavivii.
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

dru: myasi'anonga ko mwani gako, 'Aase ka la 'angelakese mwa gako. 'Aase laalra ko kisodamini na ma'akakwanga swavivii bwa'ay ko soi'anini.
english: The next day at school, 'Aase arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

dru: 'Aase piingavanga komo laya ko soi'anini, la 'apobaka, no biilanenga ko 'angiamece mikake na ma'akakwanga, mabeabee ko booane ladoo kibaka pasodame na ma'akakwanga.
english: 'Aase apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.
My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

dru: 'avalavalakilika, tatava silamama no masongo ka laobalate, wamece na kwange si livase.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

dru: leleapininga laameco ko alopini na bee 'abee.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

dru: no kadromane ka valisane, kadromane ka ava'a, la 'ikay na 'atiko'asini.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

dru: kinadro ka 'iyakay tacekecekelane balate saoda'ane lwapii ko alraninabee, bway talinya nane.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

dru: 'ataleese kake makavalay tatavane, ko 'angeese tatavane mwa walopomya.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

dru: tatava la'apobaka ano patekedrisonga ka koameamece mosoa mya.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

dru: tacekecekelane na sa'oalalay ka waigo'o wathii malra na bee, waigo'o paytha na sathe'ethe'ee si sata'eta'ene.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

dru: tatavi nakoa ka waigo'o paytha na sathe'ethe'e, tatava ka 'apobaka, "kikay ka saakai malra na tiko'ase, paingcege kimade cengele o'ongini na bee athii made ka pa'ikay kimade ko dadaanini."
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

dru: pwaikay koibongo 'angese na tamatama mwa walopo mya, pava'iyane kake kica'oane paytha na dreese, isipyale ko tidresili ka ladoonga malra na bee.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

dru: cengelini ki tatava ka la 'apobaka, no biilanenga ka 'isadraya koso ikamani ko wadodoonga walwalopo.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

dru: nakaynga ka la patekedrenga kakae, laaba kake ko panaili, kisa'apaa tatavane walopo.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

dru: kelayname baivi ka la alra kiname ko alraname bebee lwapii talinamiyanane.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

dru: tatava ka 'apobaka, "takabeabee na sobalibalini mitya ki lamama doo kita malra 'angiyadraw na bee."
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

dru: maeae ko mwali gako ka 'iyasolodrane kake.
english: I was late for school this morning.

dru: ko mwali gako ka, maymo kake wamece na kabange.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

dru: ko solatiname ka, 'angiese kake ko sito cengele na solate.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

dru: ko sikingi name ka, ko soi'aniname ka kyasedame nakowa ko 'ipicili si sadrisdrisili.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

dru: la'osayli ka tangoco, valakini nyane na thakongadavane.
english: My good friend's name is tangoco, and he is also an thakongadavane child.
We study together in the kongadavane tribe.

dru: 'atalese kiname ta'aese biciingi na maodrange timalolwai, sawkwa kiname igo'o thwakongadavadavane.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the thakongadavane proficiently.

dru: ma'agae kake si lakamite kake, ki tangoco ka la'aticane si lakaylai.
english: I am tall and overweight, while tangoco is short and thin.

dru: ki tangoco ka sapaovikane, madalame kita nyane.
english: tangoco is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

dru: sesane gako ka ta'ongdokane, gako ka tyadrao pyatha na ma'akawmawmale na 'ongdo.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

dru: 'iyakay na mabilibilibili makakadang na malri tyaidai wayogi si wapana.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

dru: ko tidayli ka, 'iyaevese kake, pakoili ka lapasawkowa 'apo'aydri.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.
But I stood up and continued running forward.

dru: ko kelayli ta'iegegane ka ko lawcococao ka lakabeabee.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

dru: kwamili iya na mwasakaesa ka, makasi mabeabe kake, nikwani ka paepengenga kake ma'akawmaomale.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

dru: kosi'a ki tatavi nakowa si kake ka amowa kiname swapepeale tatavane.legeageane.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

dru: kidra ka matikaykay namiya, da'ane cai ka maboto.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

dru: 'ako syozingini cai ka, syalikai cai 'ievese molili.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

dru: ki tatava ka wamece na nwange na bwate si thaviki bwa'ay tatavane.legeageane.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

dru: kake si tatava ki legeageay ka 'iyakay kiname tasyaekane mababaka, kini ka lapatikaykaykay na mawlay.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

dru: ko 'abee myali ka, ki tatava. legeageay ka pakileve nakowa patekedrenga koso mya, lakagi'i na engedelaniso mya.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

dru: la'apobaka kake, no magi'ininga drapalini ki tatava legeageay ka, nobilanenga ka ni'awkay da'aniname 'aangi.
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

dru: ko 2022 na cavili ka sifo ka wakaygi pwaikai na kacaysyane acini ka nodo amiya solate paikay nibongsyo.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

dru: amowakake swapepeale ko paitha pwayvikay malra na acita pa'ikay nibongsyo solate na acita "solate na acita kwacaysisyane" tacekecekelane thathabee ki legeageay·thabilane.
english: I interviewed legeageay·thabilane, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

dru: wavisi kake nyane pa'ikay na nicyobi mwa da'anidra swpepeale kibobo nyane.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

dru: kokiboboili nyane ka, la'angi'apobaka ko acini ko tayanini, laameamece nakwa paygo'o ko talinyanane, si ko tacekecekelanidra.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

dru: lakibobob kake nyane manini ka mo'ananavaniso kokela pabaythi na ace mya, ko awlane na sasolasolate ka makowace nyani.
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

dru: la'apobaka nakwa, nikwani nosyakaimade na wacyokokwane acita ka iyow 'angicege koyanimade 'apobaka ko acita, kinadro nokwakwaidra ka "le singseng," nomyani ka nikwani i'abowale madraw na sa'angingi.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Le Xian Sheng

dru: ki legeageay.thabilane ka la'apobaka, "ki kai syakai na wakacaysisyane solata na acita ka amani kini ko tyakikadringay ko acita. kikai acili ka wadayhyo na ta'asakabanita, ta'athakada'anita, ta'acwanita, samangane lakadradradrawo na cekelita silape pasivivi na acita."
english: legeageay.thabilane said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

dru: kosi'a ka 'angiese kake takawngane mwa talangalangane na lacenge lwangalangay na lacenge.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

dru: madalame kita takawngane ko talangalanganidra, na tavangolo si abai madrao na walangai, madrao na lawcocao na 'awkay lwavalava ko tidamadamaidra.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and rice cake, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

dru: ko do'oini na okoco si kapagane ka sawkowa maagi'i nokwanimade, la syakay na valisane tidamay na makao si bee, ko sangyaemini ka la'awkay madraw na babaa, lakaesale 'awkay talangalanganiname matilibi.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

dru: ki takawngo no do'odo'oyni ka, la'ikay kake cigi'ane kwakwao, "kikai lelacenge ka 'angidadoko'iname, 'angikakamani 'atawmomo ipawa na sabo'owane, ngwalra ibonga lwangay!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

dru: ko ma'akakwanga ka laybongo malangay, ki takaongo ka la'apobaka, "nikwani ka amani koso ko pasopapaa."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

dru: kikai 'ongdo ka, lakica'owane kake igo'o na kacaysyane na ma'aka sadodoko'onga si kanekanita na igilane, la lavalvanga kake na walangalangai ko baylanenini.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

dru: cengelimade takawngane lasawkwa madalame na makacaysyane na akanakane ka, sawkwa kake 'angimamada si sapelengane.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
